const GEOGRAPHY_EDEXCEL_PRACTICE = {
  'T1': {
    name: 'Tectonic Processes & Hazards',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "hazard profile".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A technique/method of comparing hazards (1)\n• Using characteristics such as magnitude, speed of onset, duration, areal extent, frequency, predictability (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "seismicity".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The occurrence/frequency of earthquakes (1)\n• In a given region/area (1)' },
      { q: 'State two pieces of evidence that support the theory of continental drift.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Jigsaw fit of continents e.g. South America and Africa (1)\n• Matching fossil records across continents e.g. Mesosaurus (1)\n• Matching rock types/geological structures (1)\n• Glacial deposits in tropical locations (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "disaster".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A hazard event that causes significant damage/loss of life (1)\n• Exceeds the ability of the affected community to cope using its own resources (1)' },
      { q: 'Identify two secondary hazards associated with earthquakes.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Tsunami (1)\n• Landslides/avalanches (1)\n• Liquefaction (1)\n• Fires from ruptured gas mains (1)' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of shield volcanoes.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Wide base/gently sloping sides (1)\n• Formed from basaltic/low-viscosity lava (1)\n• Non-explosive/effusive eruptions (1)\n• Found at hotspots or divergent boundaries (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by "magma plume".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• A column/body of hot mantle material (1)\n• Rising from deep within the mantle/core-mantle boundary (1)\n• Creates volcanic activity at the surface/hotspot (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the Pressure and Release (PAR) model.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• A model that explains how disasters occur (1)\n• When natural hazards affect vulnerable people (1)\n• Vulnerability is rooted in social/economic/political processes (1)\n• Disaster = hazard x vulnerability (1)' },
      { q: 'State three factors that influence volcanic hazard severity.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Viscosity of magma/silica content (1)\n• Gas content of magma (1)\n• Volume of material erupted (1)\n• Population density nearby (1)\n• Preparedness/warning systems (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between the Richter and Moment Magnitude scales.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Richter measures amplitude of seismic waves (1)\n• Moment Magnitude measures total energy released (1)\n• Moment Magnitude is more accurate for large earthquakes/does not plateau (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain how convection currents drive tectonic plate movement.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Radioactive decay in the core generates heat (1)\n• Hot material rises in the mantle as it is less dense (1)\n• Spreads laterally beneath the lithosphere, dragging plates (1)\n• Cools and sinks back down creating circular convection cells (1)\n• Ridge push and slab pull also contribute to plate motion (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why some earthquakes cause more damage than others.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Magnitude/energy released affects shaking intensity (1)\n• Depth of focus — shallow focus earthquakes cause more surface damage (1)\n• Distance from epicentre — closer settlements experience stronger shaking (1)\n• Population density affects number of casualties (1)\n• Building quality/earthquake-resistant design (1)\n• Level of preparedness, warning systems and emergency response (1)\n• Time of day affects where people are located (1)\n• Secondary hazards such as tsunamis or liquefaction (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the process of subduction at a destructive plate boundary.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Two plates converge/move towards each other (1)\n• Denser oceanic plate is forced beneath the less dense continental plate (1)\n• Creates a deep ocean trench at the point of subduction (1)\n• Friction and increasing pressure cause the oceanic plate to melt (1)\n• Magma rises to form volcanic arc/fold mountains on the overriding plate (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two reasons why people continue to live in tectonically active areas.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Fertile volcanic soils support agriculture/livelihoods (1)\n• Geothermal energy provides cheap/renewable power (1)\n• Tourism to volcanic landscapes creates employment (1)\n• Mineral resources such as gold, copper can be mined (1)\n• Lack of financial resources to relocate (1)\n• Cultural/historical attachment to place (1)\n• Perception that risk is low/acceptable (1)' },
      { q: 'Draw and annotate a diagram to show the features found at a convergent plate boundary.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Diagram showing two plates moving together (1)\n• Oceanic plate subducting beneath continental plate (1)\n• Ocean trench labelled at point of subduction (1)\n• Benioff zone/area of earthquake foci marked (1)\n• Volcanic arc/mountains on overriding plate (1)\n• Rising magma from melting oceanic plate shown (1)\n• Accretionary wedge/fold mountains labelled (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how slab pull contributes to plate tectonics.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• At subduction zones, the oceanic plate sinks into the mantle (1)\n• The cold, dense slab pulls the rest of the plate behind it (1)\n• Considered the dominant driving force of plate motion (1)\n• Creates tension that can cause rifting at the trailing edge (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of technology in predicting tectonic hazards.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Seismometers detect foreshocks/changes in seismic activity (1)\n• GPS monitors ground deformation/plate movement (1)\n• Satellite remote sensing detects changes in ground surface/thermal anomalies (1)\n• Tiltmeters and gas sensors monitor volcanic activity (1)\n• Tsunami warning systems use ocean floor sensors (1)\n• Earthquake prediction remains unreliable despite technology (1)\n• Volcanic eruptions are more successfully predicted using monitoring equipment (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why volcanic eruptions at constructive plate boundaries differ from those at destructive boundaries.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Constructive boundaries produce basaltic/low-viscosity magma (1)\n• Low silica content means less gas trapped (1)\n• Eruptions are effusive/gentle with lava flows (1)\n• Destructive boundaries produce andesitic/rhyolitic high-viscosity magma (1)\n• High silica content traps gas, building pressure (1)\n• Eruptions are explosive with pyroclastic flows and ash (1)\n• Different magma compositions due to different processes — partial melting vs decompression melting (1)' },
      { q: 'Sketch and annotate a diagram showing the global distribution of earthquakes and volcanoes.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• World map outline with plate boundaries shown (1)\n• Ring of Fire around Pacific labelled (1)\n• Mid-Atlantic Ridge/constructive boundary marked (1)\n• Earthquakes concentrated along plate boundaries (1)\n• Intra-plate hotspot volcanoes shown e.g. Hawaii (1)\n• Destructive boundary zones marked e.g. Andes, Japan (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how liquefaction occurs during an earthquake.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Seismic waves cause vibration of saturated/waterlogged soils (1)\n• Soil particles lose contact with each other (1)\n• Water pressure between grains increases (1)\n• Solid ground behaves like liquid, losing bearing capacity (1)\n• Buildings sink/tilt as foundations fail (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the hazard management cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Mitigation — actions to reduce the severity or impact of a hazard before it occurs (1)\n• Preparedness — planning and training to respond effectively (1)\n• Response — immediate actions during and after the event to save lives (1)\n• Recovery — short and long-term rebuilding and restoration (1)\n• The cycle is continuous — lessons from one event inform future mitigation (1)\n• Different stakeholders play different roles at each stage (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how a tsunami is generated by a submarine earthquake.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Earthquake occurs on a fault beneath the ocean floor (1)\n• Vertical displacement of the sea floor displaces a large volume of water (1)\n• Energy propagates outward as waves with long wavelength in deep water (1)\n• Waves slow and increase in height as they approach shallow coastal areas (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between intra-plate and inter-plate earthquakes.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Inter-plate earthquakes occur at plate boundaries (1)\n• Caused by friction and stress between moving plates (1)\n• Intra-plate earthquakes occur within the interior of a plate (1)\n• May be caused by ancient fault reactivation, hotspots or mantle plume activity (1)\n• Intra-plate earthquakes are less frequent but can still be powerful (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of governance in managing tectonic hazards.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Governments set building codes/regulations for earthquake-resistant construction (1)\n• Land-use planning can restrict development in high-risk zones (1)\n• Investment in monitoring and early warning systems (1)\n• Emergency response planning and training (1)\n• International aid coordination for developing countries (1)\n• Corruption/weak governance can reduce effectiveness of hazard management (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how the level of development of a country affects its vulnerability to tectonic hazards.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Wealthier countries can invest in earthquake-resistant infrastructure (1)\n• Better emergency services and healthcare reduce mortality (1)\n• Insurance availability enables faster economic recovery (1)\n• Education and communication systems improve preparedness (1)\n• Developing countries may have higher population density in hazard zones (1)\n• Less capacity to invest in monitoring technology and warning systems (1)\n• Rapid urbanisation in developing countries increases exposure (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which volcanic hazards can be successfully managed.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with balanced argument, supported by specific examples. Shows understanding that management success varies by context.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with examples but may be one-sided or lack detail.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements with limited understanding.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Monitoring technology (seismometers, gas sensors, tiltmeters) can predict eruptions\n• Evacuation plans have saved lives e.g. Mount Pinatubo 1991\n• Land-use zoning can reduce exposure\n• Lava diversion barriers have had limited success e.g. Heimaey, Iceland 1973\n• Pyroclastic flows remain largely unmanageable\n• Success depends on level of development and governance\n• Some eruptions are unpredictable in timing and scale\n• Community preparedness and education are vital' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that earthquakes are more dangerous than volcanic eruptions.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment comparing both hazard types with specific examples. Reaches a supported conclusion.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some comparison with examples but may lack balance or depth.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements with limited comparison.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Earthquakes are unpredictable and give no warning\n• Earthquakes cause secondary hazards — tsunami, liquefaction, landslides\n• E.g. 2010 Haiti earthquake — 230,000 deaths, minimal warning\n• Volcanic eruptions can be monitored and predicted more reliably\n• E.g. Mount Pinatubo 1991 — successful evacuation saved thousands\n• However volcanic eruptions can have global climate impacts e.g. ash clouds\n• Pyroclastic flows are lethal and hard to escape\n• Death toll depends on development level, not just hazard type\n• Both hazard types vary greatly in magnitude and impact' },
      { q: 'Assess the importance of technology in reducing the impact of tectonic hazards.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of technologys role with specific examples. Considers limitations and compares with other approaches.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples but may lack balance.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic points with limited understanding.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Seismometers, GPS, InSAR satellite monitoring track plate movements\n• Pacific Tsunami Warning Centre has reduced tsunami deaths\n• Earthquake-resistant engineering (base isolation, cross-bracing) reduces structural damage\n• GIS mapping identifies hazard zones for planning\n• Technology alone is insufficient — needs governance, education, preparedness\n• Developing countries may lack resources to implement technology\n• Earthquake prediction remains unreliable\n• Community-level preparedness equally important\n• E.g. Japan — highly technological but 2011 tsunami still caused 18,000+ deaths' },
      { q: 'Assess the reasons why the impacts of tectonic hazards vary between countries at different levels of development.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific comparative examples. Considers multiple factors and reaches supported conclusion.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with examples but may lack depth or balance.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements with limited development.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Infrastructure quality — earthquake-resistant buildings in Japan vs unreinforced masonry in Nepal\n• Emergency services capacity and response times\n• Education and public awareness of hazard procedures\n• Economic resources for recovery and reconstruction\n• Insurance availability and penetration rates\n• Governance quality and corruption levels\n• Population density and urbanisation patterns\n• E.g. Compare 2010 Haiti (7.0, 230,000 deaths) with 2010 Chile (8.8, 525 deaths)\n• However, high-magnitude events can overwhelm even wealthy nations e.g. Japan 2011' },
      { q: 'Explain the different plate tectonic theories and assess which best explains plate movement.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Clear explanation of multiple theories with a supported assessment of their relative importance.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Explains theories but assessment may be limited.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic description of one or two theories.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Convection currents — heat from radioactive decay drives circulation in mantle\n• Ridge push — elevated mid-ocean ridges push plates away under gravity\n• Slab pull — dense subducting slabs pull plates into the mantle\n• Basal drag — friction between mantle flow and base of lithosphere\n• Slab pull considered the dominant mechanism by most geophysicists\n• Evidence from plate velocity correlations with subduction zone length\n• Likely a combination of forces rather than single mechanism\n• Original Wegener hypothesis and subsequent evidence from palaeomagnetism' },
      { q: 'Draw an annotated diagram to explain the formation of a hotspot volcano and assess the evidence for mantle plumes.', marks: 9, diagram: true, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Well-drawn diagram with clear annotations and a supported assessment of evidence.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Diagram present with some annotation, partial assessment.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic diagram or written response only.\n\nIndicative content:\nDiagram should show:\n• Fixed mantle plume rising from deep mantle\n• Plate moving over the stationary hotspot\n• Chain of volcanic islands with age progression\n• Active volcano over current plume position\n• Extinct/eroded volcanoes further from plume\nAssessment:\n• Hawaiian island chain as classic evidence — age increases with distance\n• Yellowstone hotspot track across North America\n• Some scientists question existence of deep mantle plumes\n• Alternative shallow-source models proposed\n• Seismic tomography provides some imaging evidence' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which tectonic hazard profiles are useful for hazard management.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of hazard profiles with specific examples of usefulness and limitations.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about hazard profiles.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Hazard profiles compare characteristics: magnitude, speed of onset, duration, areal extent, frequency, predictability\n• Allow comparison between different hazard types for prioritisation\n• Inform resource allocation and planning decisions\n• Help identify which hazards need most investment in prediction\n• However, profiles are generalised — individual events may differ\n• Do not account for vulnerability or resilience of populations\n• Static tool — does not account for changing risk over time\n• Most useful when combined with other approaches such as risk mapping' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of international organisations in managing tectonic hazards.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of organisations and their effectiveness.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with examples but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about international aid.\n\nIndicative content:\n• UN agencies coordinate disaster response e.g. OCHA, UNDP\n• World Bank/IMF provide financial support for recovery\n• NGOs (Red Cross, MSF) deliver immediate humanitarian aid\n• Sendai Framework sets international targets for disaster risk reduction\n• Criticism of slow response times and bureaucratic delays\n• Aid dependency can undermine local capacity building\n• Coordination challenges between multiple agencies\n• Effectiveness depends on host government cooperation\n• E.g. International response to 2015 Nepal earthquake' },
      { q: 'Assess the significance of mega-disasters in tectonic hazard management.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of mega-disasters with specific examples and clear reasoning.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant points with examples but lacks depth.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic understanding of mega-disasters.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Mega-disasters overwhelm national response capacity\n• E.g. 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami — 230,000 deaths across multiple countries\n• E.g. 2011 Tohoku earthquake — triggered nuclear disaster at Fukushima\n• Can cause global economic impacts through supply chain disruption\n• Drive policy changes and improved international cooperation\n• Led to creation of Indian Ocean Tsunami Warning System\n• Highlight limitations of technology and preparation\n• Raise questions about acceptable risk in developed nations\n• Insurance industry impacts and financial exposure' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which prediction and forecasting can reduce the impact of tectonic hazards.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment distinguishing prediction from forecasting, with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant assessment but may confuse terms or lack examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic points about prediction.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Prediction = stating when and where a specific event will occur (not yet reliable for earthquakes)\n• Forecasting = estimating probability of events occurring in an area over time\n• Volcanic eruptions more successfully predicted using monitoring\n• E.g. Pinatubo 1991 — precursor signs enabled evacuation\n• Earthquake prediction remains unreliable despite research\n• Tsunami warning systems effective once earthquake detected\n• Seismic gap theory used for long-term forecasting\n• Prediction alone insufficient without preparedness and response capacity\n• False alarms can reduce public trust in warnings\n• Short-term prediction vs long-term forecasting have different management uses' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the statement: "The impact of tectonic hazards depends more on human factors than physical factors."', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough and balanced evaluation with a range of specific case study evidence. Reaches a well-supported conclusion that addresses the relative importance of both sets of factors.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples but may lack balance or depth in places.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant points made but argument is underdeveloped or one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements with limited understanding.\n\nIndicative content:\nHuman factors:\n• Level of development determines infrastructure quality and emergency response\n• Governance and corruption affect building code enforcement\n• Population density and urbanisation increase exposure\n• Preparedness, education and warning systems\n• Compare Haiti 2010 (230,000 deaths) with Chile 2010 (525 deaths)\n• Land-use planning and settlement patterns\nPhysical factors:\n• Magnitude and depth of earthquake\n• Type of volcanic eruption (explosive vs effusive)\n• Speed of onset and duration\n• Secondary hazards (tsunami, lahars, pyroclastic flows)\n• Time of day and weather conditions\n• 2011 Japan tsunami — overwhelmed highly prepared nation\nConclusion should weigh both sides — likely that human factors are more important for moderate events but extreme physical events can overwhelm any level of preparation.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of different approaches to managing tectonic hazards. Use examples from contrasting locations.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation of multiple management approaches with detailed case studies from contrasting locations. Well-structured argument reaching a nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples and some contrast between locations.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited examples or lacking contrast.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points with limited evaluation.\n\nIndicative content:\nPrediction and monitoring:\n• Volcanic monitoring success at Pinatubo 1991 — 75,000 evacuated\n• Pacific Tsunami Warning System and DART buoys\n• Earthquake prediction remains unreliable\nProtection:\n• Japan — earthquake-resistant engineering, sea walls\n• Building codes in California vs poor enforcement in developing countries\n• Lava diversion barriers (Heimaey, Iceland)\nPreparedness:\n• Japan earthquake drills and public education\n• Emergency kits, evacuation routes, communication systems\n• Community-based disaster risk reduction in developing countries\nPlanning:\n• Land-use zoning to restrict development in high-risk areas\n• Insurance systems in developed vs developing countries\n• Relocation programmes\nContrasting examples:\n• Japan (developed) vs Nepal (developing)\n• Chile (middle income) vs Haiti (low income)\n• Success depends on combination of approaches, governance quality and economic resources' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that tectonic hazards will become more deadly in the future despite advances in technology.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Balanced evaluation considering multiple factors with specific evidence. Reaches a nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples but may lack balance.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant points but argument underdeveloped.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nMore deadly:\n• Rapid urbanisation increasing population in hazard zones\n• Climate change may increase secondary hazards (sea-level rise amplifies tsunami impact)\n• Megacities on fault lines e.g. Istanbul, Tokyo, Manila\n• Growing inequality means vulnerable populations increasing\n• Complex infrastructure creates cascading failure risks (Fukushima)\nLess deadly:\n• Improved monitoring technology and early warning systems\n• Better building codes and engineering solutions\n• International cooperation frameworks (Sendai)\n• Communication technology enables faster response\n• Increased scientific understanding of hazard processes\nConclusion should consider that technology helps but exposure is increasing — net effect depends on governance and investment priorities.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the extent to which understanding plate tectonic theory helps in the management of tectonic hazards.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive, well-structured discussion with detailed case study evidence. Demonstrates thorough understanding of plate tectonic theory and its management applications. Reaches a nuanced and well-supported conclusion.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples and clear structure. Some depth of analysis.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Partial discussion with some relevant points but may lack depth, range or structure.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content with limited discussion.\n\nIndicative content:\nHow theory helps management:\n• Identifies plate boundary types and associated hazard types\n• Enables hazard mapping of high-risk zones\n• Informs building codes and land-use planning\n• Supports monitoring network placement\n• Understanding of subduction processes helps volcanic eruption forecasting\n• Seismic gap theory identifies areas overdue for earthquakes\n• Palaeoseismology uses historical records to estimate recurrence intervals\nLimitations:\n• Cannot predict exact timing of earthquakes\n• Intra-plate events not fully explained by theory\n• Knowledge of processes does not prevent impacts\n• Human factors (poverty, governance) often more important than scientific knowledge\n• Theory explains why hazards occur but not when\n• E.g. 2004 Boxing Day tsunami — theory identified Sunda Trench risk but no warning system in place\nCase studies:\n• Japan — excellent theoretical understanding but 2011 still devastating\n• Iceland — monitoring based on understanding of constructive boundary\n• Nepal — known seismic risk but limited capacity to act on knowledge\nConclusion should argue that understanding is necessary but not sufficient — effective management requires governance, resources and community engagement alongside scientific knowledge.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the statement: "There is no such thing as a natural disaster, only a natural hazard." Discuss with reference to tectonic events.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Sophisticated evaluation with detailed case studies demonstrating how human factors convert hazards into disasters. Well-structured with a clear and nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples and clear argument.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited depth or range of examples.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic statements with limited understanding.\n\nIndicative content:\nHazards become disasters through human vulnerability:\n• PAR model — root causes (poverty, governance), dynamic pressures (urbanisation, deforestation), unsafe conditions (poor buildings, exposed locations)\n• Degg model — disaster occurs at intersection of hazard and vulnerability\n• Haiti 2010 — poverty, corruption, no building codes turned moderate earthquake into catastrophe\n• Social inequality means poor/marginalised communities suffer most\n• Urbanisation concentrates populations in hazard zones\n• Globalisation creates interconnected vulnerabilities\nCounter-argument — physical factors matter:\n• Mega-events overwhelm even prepared nations (Japan 2011)\n• Magnitude, depth, location are beyond human control\n• Secondary hazards add unpredictable dimensions\n• Some hazards are genuinely unavoidable regardless of preparation\nCase studies:\n• Compare Chile 2010 vs Haiti 2010 — similar hazard, vastly different disaster\n• Christchurch 2011 — developed country still significantly impacted\n• Nepal 2015 — known risk but limited capacity to prepare\n• Iceland Eyjafjallajokull 2010 — minimal local disaster but global disruption\nConclusion should engage with the philosophical point that the statement highlights the social construction of risk — disasters are largely human-made through choices about where and how we build communities, but extreme events can create disasters regardless of preparation.' },
    ],
  },

  'T2': {
    name: 'Landscape Systems, Processes & Change',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "weathering".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The breakdown/decomposition of rocks (1)\n• In situ/without transport (1)' },
      { q: 'State two types of mass movement.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Rockfall (1)\n• Rotational slumping/landslide (1)\n• Soil creep (1)\n• Mudflow (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "sediment cell".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A stretch of coastline/section of a river system (1)\n• That is a closed/self-contained system for sediment movement (1)' },
      { q: 'State two factors that affect the rate of weathering.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Rock type/lithology/mineral composition (1)\n• Climate/temperature/rainfall (1)\n• Vegetation cover (1)\n• Aspect/exposure (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "erosion".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The wearing away of rock/land surface (1)\n• By agents such as water, wind, ice and involving transport of material (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the process of freeze-thaw weathering.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Water enters cracks/joints in rock (1)\n• Water freezes and expands by approximately 9% (1)\n• Repeated freeze-thaw cycles widen cracks until rock fragments break off (1)' },
      { q: 'State three erosional processes operating at the coast.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Hydraulic action — force of water compresses air in cracks (1)\n• Abrasion — sediment thrown against cliff by waves (1)\n• Attrition — rocks collide and break into smaller, rounder pieces (1)\n• Corrosion/solution — chemical dissolving of rock by seawater (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "dynamic equilibrium" in a landscape system.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• A state of balance within a system (1)\n• Where inputs and outputs are roughly equal (1)\n• If one element changes, the system adjusts to restore balance (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe two features of constructive waves.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Low wave height/long wavelength (1)\n• Strong swash relative to backwash (1)\n• Low frequency (6-8 per minute) (1)\n• Lead to deposition/beach building (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "littoral zone".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The area of the coast/shoreline (1)\n• Between the high and low tide marks/affected by wave action (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain how geological structure influences coastal landforms.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Rock type affects resistance to erosion — hard rocks form headlands, soft rocks form bays (1)\n• Concordant coasts have rock strata parallel to shore — uniform coastline (1)\n• Discordant coasts have strata at right angles — headlands and bays (1)\n• Joint and fault patterns create lines of weakness exploited by erosion (1)\n• Bedding planes affect cliff stability and mass movement (1)\n• Dip of strata affects cliff profile — seaward dip creates steep cliffs (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the formation of a wave-cut platform.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Waves attack the base of the cliff through erosion (hydraulic action, abrasion) (1)\n• A wave-cut notch forms at the base of the cliff (1)\n• Overhanging rock above becomes unsupported and collapses (1)\n• Cliff retreats leaving a gently sloping wave-cut platform exposed at low tide (1)\n• Process repeats causing progressive cliff retreat (1)' },
      { q: 'Draw and annotate a diagram showing the formation of a spit.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Diagram showing coastline with change in direction (1)\n• Longshore drift direction indicated with arrows (1)\n• Sediment deposited beyond the change in coastline direction (1)\n• Spit extends into open water (1)\n• Curved/recurved end due to wave refraction or secondary wind direction (1)\n• Sheltered area behind spit with salt marsh/mudflats (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Hjulstrom curve shows the relationship between river velocity and sediment transport.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Shows critical erosion and deposition velocities for different particle sizes (1)\n• Clay-sized particles require high velocity to erode due to cohesion (1)\n• Sand-sized particles are easiest to erode — lowest critical velocity (1)\n• Larger particles (gravel, boulders) need progressively higher velocities to erode (1)\n• Transport velocity is lower than erosion velocity for most particles (1)\n• Deposition occurs when velocity falls below the settling velocity for each particle size (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the formation of a waterfall and plunge pool.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• River flows over band of resistant rock overlying softer rock (1)\n• Softer rock beneath is eroded more quickly by hydraulic action and abrasion (1)\n• Undercutting creates an overhang of hard rock (1)\n• Overhang collapses and plunge pool deepens at the base through erosion (1)\n• Waterfall retreats upstream leaving a gorge (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two processes of sediment transport in rivers.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Traction — large boulders rolled along the river bed by flow (1)\n• Saltation — smaller particles bounced along the bed in a hopping motion (1)\n• Suspension — fine particles carried within the water flow (1)\n• Solution — dissolved minerals carried in the water (1)\nCredit explanation of the process and how particle size relates to method (max 2 marks per process)' },
      { q: 'Explain how climate affects landscape systems.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Temperature determines dominant weathering type — freeze-thaw in periglacial, chemical in tropical (1)\n• Precipitation affects river discharge and erosion rates (1)\n• Wind speed and direction influence coastal erosion and transport (1)\n• Climate influences vegetation cover which stabilises slopes (1)\n• Seasonal variations affect processes e.g. spring meltwater increases fluvial erosion (1)\n• Past climates have shaped relict features in current landscapes (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the formation of an ox-bow lake.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Erosion on the outside bend of a meander through hydraulic action and abrasion (1)\n• Deposition on the inside bend where velocity is lower (1)\n• Meander neck narrows as erosion continues (1)\n• During flood, the river breaks through the narrow neck taking a straighter course (1)\n• Deposition seals off the old meander bend forming an ox-bow lake (1)' },
      { q: 'Draw and annotate a diagram to show the long profile of a river from source to mouth.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Diagram showing concave curve from source to mouth (1)\n• Upper course — steep gradient, V-shaped valley, waterfalls (1)\n• Middle course — moderate gradient, meanders, floodplain developing (1)\n• Lower course — gentle gradient, wide floodplain, large meanders (1)\n• Graded profile/profile of equilibrium concept indicated (1)\n• Rejuvenation features noted if applicable — knick points (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how human activity can disrupt the sediment budget of a coastal system.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Groynes trap sediment updrift, causing sediment starvation downdrift (1)\n• Sea walls prevent natural cliff erosion, reducing sediment input (1)\n• Dam construction on rivers reduces sediment delivery to the coast (1)\n• Dredging removes sediment from the nearshore zone (1)\n• Beach nourishment artificially adds sediment to the system (1)\n• Mining of sand and gravel depletes natural stores (1)\n• Can lead to increased erosion in some areas (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of systems theory as applied to landscape systems.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Landscapes operate as open systems with inputs, stores, transfers and outputs (1)\n• Inputs include precipitation, solar energy, sediment from weathering (1)\n• Outputs include sediment to the sea, evaporation, dissolved minerals (1)\n• Negative feedback maintains equilibrium — system adjusts to restore balance (1)\n• Positive feedback can push system towards new equilibrium (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how vegetation influences slope processes.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Roots bind soil particles together, increasing cohesion and slope stability (1)\n• Interception reduces the impact of rainfall on the soil surface (1)\n• Transpiration removes water from soil, reducing weight and pore water pressure (1)\n• Removal of vegetation through deforestation increases erosion and mass movement risk (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how longshore drift operates.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Waves approach the coast at an angle determined by prevailing wind direction (1)\n• Swash carries sediment up the beach at this angle (1)\n• Backwash carries sediment straight back down the beach under gravity (1)\n• Net effect is a zigzag movement of sediment along the coast (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the differences between hard and soft engineering approaches to coastal management.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Hard engineering uses artificial structures to protect the coast e.g. sea walls, groynes, rock armour (1)\n• Soft engineering works with natural processes e.g. beach nourishment, managed retreat, dune regeneration (1)\n• Hard engineering is expensive to build and maintain (1)\n• Soft engineering is often more sustainable and cost-effective long-term (1)\n• Hard engineering can cause problems elsewhere by disrupting sediment transport (1)\n• Soft engineering may not provide sufficient protection in high-energy environments (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of weathering in providing sediment to landscape systems.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Physical weathering breaks rock into smaller fragments e.g. freeze-thaw, salt crystallisation (1)\n• Chemical weathering dissolves minerals e.g. carbonation of limestone (1)\n• Biological weathering from root growth and organic acids (1)\n• Weathered material is then available for transport by mass movement, rivers and waves (1)\n• Rate of sediment production depends on rock type, climate and vegetation (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the relative importance of marine and sub-aerial processes in shaping the coastline.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment of both process types with specific examples. Reaches a supported conclusion about relative importance.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples but may lack balance.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about coastal processes.\n\nIndicative content:\nMarine processes:\n• Wave erosion — hydraulic action, abrasion create cliffs, caves, arches, stacks\n• Longshore drift transports sediment to form spits, bars, tombolos\n• Wave energy and fetch determine erosion rates\n• Tidal range affects zone of erosion\nSub-aerial processes:\n• Weathering weakens cliff face — freeze-thaw, salt crystallisation, chemical\n• Mass movement — rotational slumping, rockfalls reshape cliff profiles\n• Runoff and infiltration affect slope stability\n• Vegetation stabilises or destabilises slopes\n• Often work together — marine erosion at base, sub-aerial above\n• Relative importance depends on geology and climate' },
      { q: 'Assess the success of coastal management strategies at a named location.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment of specific management strategies at a named location with evaluation of effectiveness.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with reference to a location but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about coastal management.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Named location required e.g. Holderness Coast, Lyme Regis, Mappleton\n• Description of strategies used e.g. groynes, rock armour, sea walls, managed retreat\n• Assessment of effectiveness — has erosion been reduced? At what cost?\n• Unintended consequences e.g. increased erosion downdrift\n• Cost-benefit analysis considerations\n• Social impacts — some areas protected, others abandoned\n• Environmental impacts of hard engineering\n• Long-term sustainability questioned\n• Conflict between stakeholders over management approaches' },
      { q: 'Assess the factors that influence the development of river landforms.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of multiple factors with specific examples of landforms. Considers interrelationships between factors.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some relevant factors discussed with examples.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about river landforms.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Discharge and velocity determine erosive power\n• Gradient/slope steepness affects flow characteristics\n• Rock type and geology — resistant vs non-resistant creates differential erosion\n• Sediment load — size and quantity affects deposition patterns\n• Climate — precipitation and temperature influence discharge regime\n• Vegetation — stabilises banks and reduces erosion\n• Human activity — dams, urbanisation, channelisation alter natural processes\n• Time — landscape evolution through stages of development\n• Examples: waterfalls (geology), meanders (velocity/gradient), floodplains (discharge/deposition)' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that human activity is the main cause of coastal erosion.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment weighing human and natural factors with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nHuman causes:\n• Coastal defences disrupt sediment transport causing downdrift erosion\n• Dam construction reduces fluvial sediment supply to coast\n• Dredging and sand mining remove material\n• Climate change (anthropogenic) raising sea levels and storm intensity\n• Development on coastal land increases exposure\nNatural causes:\n• Wave energy and storm frequency\n• Geological structure and rock type\n• Sea level change (isostatic and eustatic)\n• Natural sediment supply variations\n• Currents and tidal processes\nConclusion: natural processes dominate overall but human activity increasingly important and can accelerate rates of erosion significantly' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of geology in determining landscape character.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific examples showing how geology shapes different landscapes.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with examples but may lack range.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about geology and landscapes.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Lithology — rock hardness determines erosion resistance\n• Limestone creates karst topography — caves, gorges, pavements\n• Granite creates tor-topped moorland landscapes\n• Clay produces gentle rolling landscapes\n• Structure — folding and faulting create escarpments and valleys\n• Permeability affects drainage patterns and valley formation\n• Bedding planes and joints create lines of weakness\n• However, climate and time are also important\n• Same rock type can produce different landscapes in different climates\n• Past geological history (glaciation) also shapes current landscape' },
      { q: 'Assess the effectiveness of Shoreline Management Plans (SMPs) in managing coastal change.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment of SMPs with specific examples and evaluation of effectiveness.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic understanding of SMPs.\n\nIndicative content:\n• SMPs divide coast into sediment cells and sub-cells for strategic planning\n• Four policy options: hold the line, advance the line, managed retreat, no active intervention\n• Enable long-term planning over 20, 50, 100 year timescales\n• Consider economic, environmental and social factors\n• Successful in coordinating management across local authority boundaries\n• However, managed retreat controversial — e.g. Happisburgh, Norfolk\n• Conflict between economic value and cost of protection\n• Compensation issues for property owners in retreat zones\n• May not adequately account for climate change impacts\n• Political pressure can override evidence-based decisions' },
      { q: 'Assess the importance of sea-level change in shaping coastal landscapes.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment covering different types of sea-level change with specific landscape examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about sea-level change.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Eustatic change — global sea level change due to ice volume changes\n• Isostatic change — local land level change due to ice loading/unloading\n• Rising sea levels create rias (drowned river valleys) and fjords (drowned glacial valleys)\n• Falling sea levels create raised beaches and relict cliff lines\n• Current sea-level rise threatening low-lying coasts worldwide\n• Past sea-level changes explain features found above/below current sea level\n• Dalmatian coastline as example of submergent coast\n• Scandinavian coastlines showing isostatic rebound\n• Important but interacts with geology, wave processes and human activity' },
      { q: 'Assess the impacts of river flooding on people and the environment.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment of both social/economic and environmental impacts with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about flooding.\n\nIndicative content:\nNegative impacts on people:\n• Loss of life and injury\n• Property damage and financial losses\n• Displacement and homelessness\n• Disruption to transport, business and services\n• Psychological trauma and stress\nPositive/environmental impacts:\n• Floodplain deposition replenishes fertile soils\n• Wetland habitats benefit from periodic flooding\n• Groundwater recharge during flood events\n• Natural sediment redistribution maintains ecosystem health\nNamed example:\n• E.g. UK winter floods 2015-16, Bangladesh, Mississippi\n• Impact severity depends on development level, flood defences, warning systems' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of mass movement in shaping landscapes.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of different mass movement types and their landscape impacts.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with examples.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Rockfall creates scree slopes at base of cliffs\n• Rotational slumping creates stepped/terraced cliff profiles\n• Soil creep causes slow downhill movement — terracettes on slopes\n• Mudflows/debris flows can reshape valleys rapidly\n• Landslides can dam rivers creating temporary lakes\n• Triggers include heavy rainfall, earthquakes, freeze-thaw, undercutting\n• Coastal mass movement contributes sediment to the system\n• Importance varies with climate, geology and slope angle\n• Often works in combination with other processes — weathering weakens, mass movement transports' },
      { q: 'Assess the sustainability of different river flood management strategies.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment comparing hard and soft approaches with evaluation of sustainability.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about flood management.\n\nIndicative content:\nHard engineering:\n• Embankments/levees — protect adjacent land but increase risk downstream\n• Channelisation increases velocity, transferring flood risk\n• Dams regulate flow but expensive, environmental impacts, sedimentation\n• Not sustainable long-term — ongoing maintenance costs\nSoft engineering:\n• Floodplain zoning — sustainable but restricts land use\n• Afforestation — increases interception, reduces runoff\n• Washlands/flood storage areas — work with natural processes\n• Sustainable drainage systems (SuDS) in urban areas\n• River restoration/re-meandering — e.g. River Skerne, Darlington\nConclusion: combination approach most sustainable — soft engineering where possible, hard engineering for critical infrastructure' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the extent to which coastal landscapes are shaped by physical processes rather than human activity.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with a range of specific examples. Considers the interplay between physical and human factors. Reaches a nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples but may lack balance.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant points but underdeveloped argument.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nPhysical processes:\n• Wave erosion creates cliffs, caves, arches, stacks\n• Longshore drift forms spits, bars, tombolos\n• Weathering and mass movement shape cliff profiles\n• Sea-level change creates rias, fjords, raised beaches\n• Geological structure determines coastline shape\n• Storm events cause rapid change\nHuman activity:\n• Coastal defences alter erosion and deposition patterns\n• Urbanisation and development modify natural processes\n• Climate change (anthropogenic) raising sea levels\n• Pollution affects biological weathering rates\n• Tourism and recreation pressure on dune systems\n• Dam construction reduces sediment supply\nConclusion: physical processes are the primary drivers but human activity is increasingly significant, particularly through climate change and coastal management interventions.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that river landscapes are best understood as systems.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation of systems approach with specific examples. Considers strengths and limitations of this perspective.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be descriptive.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nStrengths of systems approach:\n• Identifies inputs (precipitation), stores (lakes, aquifers), transfers (runoff) and outputs (evaporation, to sea)\n• Explains how changes in one part affect the whole system\n• Dynamic equilibrium concept explains landscape adjustment\n• Feedback mechanisms explain self-regulation\n• Sediment budget framework useful for management\n• Water balance equation quantifies system components\nLimitations:\n• Oversimplifies complex reality\n• Difficult to define system boundaries precisely\n• Does not adequately account for human interventions\n• Timescale issues — different processes operate over different periods\n• May not capture catastrophic events and rapid change\n• Cultural and social factors not easily incorporated\nConclusion: systems approach is valuable as a framework but has limitations — best used alongside historical, process-based and human geography perspectives.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the challenges of managing landscapes that cross administrative boundaries.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed examples showing boundary challenges. Well-structured argument.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited examples.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Sediment cells cross local authority boundaries\n• Management in one area affects erosion/deposition elsewhere\n• Conflicting priorities between adjacent councils\n• Shoreline Management Plans attempt to coordinate across boundaries\n• River catchments cross multiple administrative areas\n• Upstream land use affects downstream flooding\n• EU directives (Water Framework Directive) provide cross-boundary framework\n• Coastal concordats and partnerships attempt coordination\n• International boundaries add complexity e.g. transboundary rivers\n• Funding inequalities between authorities\n• Democratic accountability — who decides and who pays?\n• Named examples: Holderness Coast, Solent, Thames Estuary\n• Integrated Coastal Zone Management (ICZM) approach\nConclusion: significant challenges exist but cooperative frameworks improving — success depends on political will and adequate funding.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the factors that influence the rate and type of landscape change over time.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with a wide range of factors and detailed examples across different timescales. Demonstrates understanding of interrelationships between factors.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples and clear structure.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Partial discussion with some relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nPhysical factors:\n• Geology — lithology and structure determine resistance and landscape form\n• Climate — temperature and precipitation drive weathering and erosion rates\n• Relief — gradient affects flow velocity and mass movement potential\n• Vegetation — stabilises slopes, intercepts rainfall\n• Sea-level change — creates new landforms and modifies existing ones\n• Glaciation — past ice ages have profoundly shaped UK landscape\nHuman factors:\n• Deforestation increases erosion rates\n• Urbanisation alters drainage patterns\n• Coastal and river management interventions\n• Agriculture — ploughing, drainage, land clearance\n• Climate change accelerating rates of change\nTemporal factors:\n• Catastrophic events cause rapid change (storms, floods, earthquakes)\n• Gradual processes operate over centuries/millennia\n• Landscape evolution models e.g. Davis cycle of erosion\n• Relict features from past processes\n• Feedback mechanisms — positive feedback accelerates change, negative slows it\nCase studies from contrasting environments showing different rates and types of change. Conclusion should emphasise the interconnected nature of factors and the importance of timescale in understanding landscape change.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of different strategies for managing coastal retreat at a named location or locations.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation of multiple strategies at named locations with detailed evidence and a nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited detail.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nNamed locations required e.g.:\n• Holderness Coast — fastest eroding coast in Europe\n• Happisburgh, Norfolk — managed retreat controversy\n• Lyme Regis — major engineering scheme\n• Medmerry, Sussex — managed realignment\nStrategies to evaluate:\n• Hard engineering — sea walls (expensive but effective locally), groynes (trap sediment but starve downdrift), rock armour\n• Soft engineering — beach nourishment (requires repeat application), managed retreat/realignment\n• Do nothing — allow natural processes, cheapest but social consequences\nEvaluation criteria:\n• Cost-effectiveness over different timescales\n• Environmental sustainability\n• Social acceptability and equity\n• Effectiveness at reducing erosion/flooding\n• Impact on adjacent areas\n• Adaptability to climate change\nConclusion should recognise that no single approach is universally effective — combination of strategies needed, informed by local conditions, economic analysis and community engagement.' },
    ],
  },

  'T3': {
    name: 'The Water Cycle & Water Insecurity',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "water balance".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The relationship between inputs and outputs of water in a system (1)\n• Expressed as P = Q + E +/- S (precipitation = discharge + evapotranspiration +/- storage change) (1)' },
      { q: 'State two stores of water in the global hydrological cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Oceans/seas (1)\n• Ice caps/glaciers (1)\n• Groundwater/aquifers (1)\n• Atmosphere (1)\n• Rivers/lakes (1)\n• Soil moisture (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "water insecurity".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• When people do not have reliable access to sufficient quantities (1)\n• Of clean/safe/affordable water for their needs (1)' },
      { q: 'State two human activities that affect the drainage basin water cycle.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Urbanisation increases surface runoff/reduces infiltration (1)\n• Deforestation reduces interception/evapotranspiration (1)\n• Irrigation/water abstraction (1)\n• Dam construction (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "cryosphere".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The parts of the Earth\'s surface where water is in solid/frozen form (1)\n• Includes ice sheets, glaciers, sea ice, permafrost, snow cover (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between blue water and green water.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Blue water is liquid water in rivers, lakes and aquifers (1)\n• Green water is water stored in soil and vegetation/available for evapotranspiration (1)\n• Blue water is directly accessible for human use whereas green water supports ecosystems and agriculture (1)' },
      { q: 'State three factors that affect the rate of evapotranspiration.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Temperature — higher temperatures increase evaporation (1)\n• Wind speed — increases rate of moisture removal (1)\n• Humidity — low humidity increases evapotranspiration rate (1)\n• Vegetation type and density (1)\n• Solar radiation/sunshine hours (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "baseflow".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The normal/sustained flow of a river (1)\n• Fed by groundwater seeping into the channel between rainfall events (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by "virtual water".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The total volume of water used to produce a good or service (1)\n• Includes water used in growing, processing and transporting (1)\n• Traded internationally embedded in products e.g. 15,000 litres to produce 1 kg of beef (1)' },
      { q: 'State two physical causes of water insecurity.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Climate/low or unreliable rainfall (1)\n• Seasonal drought (1)\n• Geological conditions limiting aquifer availability (1)\n• Salinisation of water sources (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain how urbanisation affects the drainage basin water cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Impermeable surfaces (concrete, tarmac) reduce infiltration (1)\n• Surface runoff increases, reaching rivers faster (1)\n• Drains and gutters act as artificial channels speeding up transfer (1)\n• Reduced soil moisture and groundwater recharge (1)\n• Less vegetation means reduced interception and evapotranspiration (1)\n• Storm hydrograph has shorter lag time and higher peak discharge (1)\n• Increased flood risk in downstream areas (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of the ocean in the global water cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Oceans store approximately 97% of Earths water — largest store (1)\n• Major source of evaporation driving atmospheric moisture (1)\n• Ocean currents redistribute heat and moisture globally (1)\n• Thermohaline circulation links ocean and climate systems (1)\n• Absorb CO2 affecting climate and indirectly the water cycle (1)\n• Sea surface temperatures influence evaporation rates and storm formation (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how climate change may affect the global water cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Higher temperatures increase evaporation rates (1)\n• Warmer atmosphere holds more moisture (7% per degree C) (1)\n• More intense precipitation events in some regions (1)\n• Increased drought frequency and severity in other regions (1)\n• Melting of glaciers and ice sheets reduces long-term freshwater storage (1)\n• Changed seasonal patterns — earlier snowmelt, altered monsoon timing (1)\n• Sea-level rise causes saltwater intrusion into freshwater aquifers (1)' },
      { q: 'Draw and annotate a storm hydrograph and explain the difference between lag time in urban and rural catchments.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Hydrograph diagram with x-axis (time) and y-axis (discharge) (1)\n• Peak discharge, rising limb, falling/recession limb labelled (1)\n• Lag time marked between peak rainfall and peak discharge (1)\n• Baseflow shown below the storm flow component (1)\n• Urban catchment has shorter lag time due to impermeable surfaces and drains (1)\n• Rural catchment has longer lag time due to infiltration, interception and slower throughflow (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why some countries face greater water insecurity than others.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Climate — arid and semi-arid regions have low water availability (1)\n• Population growth increases demand and pressure on resources (1)\n• Level of economic development affects water infrastructure (1)\n• Governance quality — corruption and mismanagement of water resources (1)\n• Transboundary water sources create geopolitical tensions (1)\n• Pollution reduces usable freshwater supply (1)\n• Agricultural practices may deplete groundwater unsustainably (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of vegetation in the water cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Interception — canopy catches precipitation before it reaches the ground (1)\n• Evapotranspiration — water absorbed by roots is released through leaves (1)\n• Root uptake — plants draw water from the soil store (1)\n• Stemflow and throughfall transfer intercepted water to the ground surface (1)\n• Vegetation increases infiltration by maintaining soil structure (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two strategies for increasing water supply.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Desalination — removing salt from seawater to produce freshwater (1)\n• Dam and reservoir construction — storing water for release when needed (1)\n• Water transfer schemes — moving water from surplus to deficit areas (1)\n• Groundwater extraction from aquifers (1)\n• Rainwater harvesting — collecting and storing rainfall (1)\n• Credit development of explanation for each strategy (max 2 marks per strategy)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the water footprint.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Total volume of freshwater used by a person, business or nation (1)\n• Includes direct water use (drinking, washing) and indirect use (virtual water in products) (1)\n• Varies greatly between countries — high in developed nations (1)\n• Useful tool for understanding true water consumption and sustainability (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of groundwater in the water cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Water infiltrates through soil and percolates into permeable rock (1)\n• Stored in aquifers — porous rock saturated with water (1)\n• Provides baseflow to rivers through slow seepage (1)\n• Major freshwater store — much larger than surface water (1)\n• Can be abstracted for human use through wells and boreholes (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the causes and impacts of over-abstraction of groundwater.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Population growth and agricultural irrigation increasing demand (1)\n• Extraction exceeds natural recharge rate (1)\n• Water table drops, requiring deeper and more expensive wells (1)\n• Land subsidence as aquifer compacts e.g. Mexico City (1)\n• Saltwater intrusion in coastal areas as freshwater is depleted (1)\n• Ecosystem damage — wetlands and springs dry up (1)\n• Long-term unsustainable — aquifer depletion can take centuries to recover (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how deforestation affects the water cycle at a local and global scale.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Local: reduced interception means more water reaches the ground (1)\n• Local: increased surface runoff and erosion (1)\n• Local: reduced evapotranspiration decreases local rainfall recycling (1)\n• Local: soil degradation reduces infiltration capacity (1)\n• Global: reduced carbon sink contributes to climate change (1)\n• Global: altered atmospheric moisture circulation patterns (1)\n• Amazon deforestation example — reduced rainfall in South America and beyond (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of a drainage basin as an open system.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Inputs — precipitation entering the catchment area (1)\n• Stores — soil moisture, groundwater, channel storage, vegetation storage (1)\n• Transfers — infiltration, throughflow, overland flow, percolation, stemflow (1)\n• Outputs — evapotranspiration, river discharge to the sea (1)\n• Energy and matter cross the system boundary (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the physical and human causes of drought.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Physical: persistent high pressure systems blocking rainfall (1)\n• Physical: El Nino/La Nina disrupting normal precipitation patterns (1)\n• Physical: low soil moisture and depleted groundwater reserves (1)\n• Human: over-abstraction of water resources (1)\n• Human: deforestation reducing rainfall recycling (1)\n• Human: climate change altering precipitation patterns (1)\n• Human: poor water management and infrastructure (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two environmental impacts of large dam construction.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Flooding of ecosystems and habitats upstream of the dam (1)\n• Disruption of sediment transport downstream — erosion increases, delta shrinks (1)\n• Altered river flow regimes affect downstream ecosystems (1)\n• Blocking fish migration routes e.g. salmon (1)\n• Reservoir sedimentation reduces capacity over time (1)\n• Changes to water temperature and chemistry downstream (1)\nCredit development of 2 impacts (max 2 marks per impact)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of the water cycle in supporting ecosystem health.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Provides freshwater essential for all living organisms (1)\n• Maintains river flows supporting aquatic ecosystems (1)\n• Groundwater sustains wetlands and springs (1)\n• Precipitation supports terrestrial vegetation growth (1)\n• Nutrient cycling depends on water movement through soil (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the severity of the global water insecurity crisis.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific data and examples. Considers different dimensions of water insecurity.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about water problems.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Over 2 billion people lack safely managed drinking water\n• Water stress affects regions across all continents\n• Agriculture uses 70% of global freshwater — unsustainable in many areas\n• Groundwater depletion accelerating — Ogallala Aquifer, North China Plain\n• Climate change intensifying existing water stress\n• Population growth increasing demand, especially in water-scarce regions\n• Water quality issues — pollution, salinisation\n• However, some regions have surplus — the problem is distribution\n• Technology solutions exist but require investment\n• Geopolitical tensions over transboundary water resources\n• Disproportionate impact on developing countries and women/girls' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which climate change is the greatest threat to global water security.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment comparing climate change with other threats. Reaches a supported conclusion.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about climate change and water.\n\nIndicative content:\nClimate change threats:\n• Altered precipitation patterns — wetter and drier extremes\n• Glacier retreat reducing long-term water supply for billions\n• Sea-level rise causing saltwater intrusion\n• More frequent and severe droughts\n• Changed snowmelt timing affecting seasonal supply\nOther threats:\n• Population growth may be more immediate pressure\n• Pollution and contamination of freshwater sources\n• Over-abstraction of groundwater\n• Poor governance and infrastructure\n• Geopolitical conflict over shared water resources\n• Agricultural intensification and wasteful irrigation\nConclusion: climate change is a major multiplier of existing threats rather than the single greatest threat — interaction between factors is key.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of water management strategies in addressing water insecurity.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of different strategies with evaluation of their effectiveness.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic points about water management.\n\nIndicative content:\nSupply-side strategies:\n• Dams and reservoirs — e.g. Three Gorges, Aswan High\n• Desalination — growing in Middle East, expensive and energy-intensive\n• Water transfer schemes — e.g. South-North Water Transfer, China\n• Groundwater extraction\nDemand-side strategies:\n• Water pricing and metering to reduce consumption\n• Efficient irrigation e.g. drip irrigation replacing flood irrigation\n• Water recycling and reuse\n• Education and behaviour change\n• Leak reduction in supply infrastructure\nAssessment:\n• Supply strategies often large-scale with environmental and social costs\n• Demand management more sustainable but politically challenging\n• Context-specific — what works depends on local conditions\n• Combination approach needed\n• Governance quality is critical for implementation success' },
      { q: 'Assess the impacts of water insecurity on economic development.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of economic impacts with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Agriculture dependent on reliable water — crop failures cause economic loss\n• Industry requires water for manufacturing, cooling, processing\n• Health impacts of water-borne disease reduce workforce productivity\n• Time spent collecting water reduces education and economic participation (especially girls/women)\n• Water conflicts divert resources from development\n• Hydroelectric power generation depends on water availability\n• Tourism affected by water quality and availability\n• Cost of water treatment and infrastructure development\n• Water insecurity deters investment and economic growth\n• E.g. Cape Town water crisis 2018 — economic impacts on tourism and agriculture' },
      { q: 'Assess the geopolitical implications of transboundary water resources.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment with specific examples of transboundary disputes and cooperation.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic awareness of water conflicts.\n\nIndicative content:\n• River Nile — Egypt, Sudan, Ethiopia tension over Grand Renaissance Dam\n• Tigris-Euphrates — Turkey, Syria, Iraq competing demands\n• Jordan River — Israel, Palestine, Jordan long-standing disputes\n• Mekong River — China dam building affecting downstream nations\n• Aral Sea — Soviet-era irrigation diversions caused ecological catastrophe\n• International water law remains weak — no enforceable framework\n• Water can be used as political leverage or weapon\n• However, water also drives cooperation — water treaties and commissions\n• Concept of hydro-hegemony — upstream nations hold power\n• Climate change likely to intensify transboundary tensions' },
      { q: 'Assess the sustainability of large-scale water transfer schemes.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples evaluating sustainability.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• China South-North Water Transfer — largest ever, $62 billion\n• Addresses geographical mismatch between supply and demand\n• Benefits: reliable supply to water-scarce areas, supports agriculture and industry\n• Environmental concerns: ecosystem disruption in source areas\n• Energy costs of pumping water over long distances\n• Social impacts: displacement of communities\n• Creates dependency rather than addressing root causes\n• Alternative approaches may be more sustainable e.g. demand management\n• Engineering challenges and maintenance costs\n• May become less effective as climate change alters source availability' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that water insecurity is primarily a problem of governance rather than physical scarcity.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment weighing governance and physical factors with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nGovernance factors:\n• Corruption diverts funding from water infrastructure\n• Poor regulation allows pollution of water sources\n• Subsidies encourage wasteful water use in agriculture\n• Lack of investment in water treatment and distribution\n• Political instability prevents long-term planning\n• Privatisation debates — access vs profit\nPhysical scarcity:\n• Arid regions genuinely lack rainfall e.g. Sahel, Middle East\n• Seasonal variability creates periodic shortages\n• Climate change reducing glacier-fed river flows\n• Some aquifers are fossil water with no recharge\nConclusion: many areas with adequate physical water still experience insecurity due to governance failure, but some regions face genuine physical scarcity that governance alone cannot solve.' },
      { q: 'Assess the environmental consequences of human interference in the water cycle.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific examples of environmental impacts.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Dam construction — Aral Sea shrinkage, disrupted ecosystems\n• Groundwater depletion — subsidence, wetland loss\n• Deforestation — altered rainfall patterns, soil erosion\n• Urbanisation — increased flooding, pollution of waterways\n• Agricultural irrigation — salinisation, aquifer depletion\n• Pollution — eutrophication, dead zones\n• Climate change — melting cryosphere, altered precipitation\n• Water diversion — river desiccation e.g. Colorado River rarely reaches sea\n• Positive examples: wetland restoration, river rehabilitation\n• Scale of interference now affecting global water cycle functioning' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of technology in addressing water insecurity.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment of different technologies with evaluation of effectiveness and limitations.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Desalination — increasingly efficient but still energy-intensive and expensive\n• Drip irrigation — reduces agricultural water use by 30-70%\n• Water recycling and purification technology\n• Remote sensing and GIS for monitoring water resources\n• Smart meters and leak detection in distribution systems\n• Atmospheric water generators — extracting water from air\n• However, technology alone insufficient without governance and investment\n• Many technologies unaffordable for developing countries\n• Appropriate technology may be more effective than high-tech solutions\n• E.g. fog nets in Chile, sand dams in Kenya\n• Technology transfer and capacity building needed' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which agriculture is the main driver of water insecurity.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment weighing agricultural impacts against other drivers.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nAgriculture as driver:\n• Uses approximately 70% of global freshwater\n• Inefficient irrigation wastes vast quantities\n• Groundwater depletion for irrigation e.g. Ogallala Aquifer\n• Pollution from fertilisers and pesticides\n• Virtual water trade — water-intensive crops exported from water-scarce regions\n• Growing demand for water-intensive diets (meat)\nOther drivers:\n• Population growth increasing total demand\n• Industrial water use and pollution\n• Climate change altering supply patterns\n• Urbanisation concentrating demand\n• Poor governance and infrastructure\nConclusion: agriculture is the largest single user and a major driver but water insecurity results from interaction of multiple factors.' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that water conflict is inevitable as global water resources become scarcer.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with balanced argument and specific case studies. Nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nConflict likely:\n• Growing demand from population and economic growth\n• Climate change reducing supply in already stressed regions\n• Transboundary rivers create competing claims\n• History of water-related tensions — Nile, Tigris-Euphrates, Jordan\n• Water used as political weapon in conflicts\n• Upstream dam building threatening downstream nations\n• Link between water stress and political instability\nConflict not inevitable:\n• History shows more cooperation than conflict over water\n• Over 300 international water treaties exist\n• Economic interdependence incentivises cooperation\n• Technology can increase effective supply\n• Water pricing and demand management can reduce pressure\n• International institutions facilitate negotiation\n• Water too essential for all parties to allow complete breakdown\nConclusion: tension likely to increase but full-scale water wars unlikely — cooperation more probable than conflict, though localised disputes will intensify.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of international efforts to improve global water security.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed examples of international initiatives. Well-structured with nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited detail.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nInternational efforts:\n• UN SDG 6 — clean water and sanitation for all by 2030\n• World Bank funding for water infrastructure projects\n• WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme tracking progress\n• International water law and transboundary agreements\n• NGO programmes e.g. WaterAid, charity: water\n• Technology transfer and capacity building\n• WASH programmes (Water, Sanitation and Hygiene)\nEffectiveness:\n• Significant progress — billions gained access since 2000\n• However, 2 billion still lack safe drinking water\n• SDG 6 unlikely to be met by 2030\n• Funding gaps remain significant\n• Implementation depends on local governance\n• Climate change undermining progress\n• Urban-rural divide persists\n• Quality often neglected in favour of quantity metrics\n• Top-down approaches may not suit local contexts\n• Community-based approaches often more sustainable\nConclusion: progress made but insufficient pace and scale — requires sustained political commitment, increased funding and locally appropriate solutions.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the impact of climate change on the global water cycle and its implications for water security.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation linking water cycle changes to security implications with specific examples.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some relevant points but lacking depth.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nWater cycle changes:\n• Intensification — increased evaporation and precipitation rates\n• Spatial redistribution — wet areas wetter, dry areas drier\n• Cryosphere decline — glacier retreat, earlier snowmelt, permafrost thaw\n• Sea-level rise and saltwater intrusion\n• Changed monsoon patterns and ENSO intensity\n• More extreme events — floods and droughts\nWater security implications:\n• Glacier-dependent populations face long-term supply decline (Himalayas, Andes)\n• Increased flood risk threatening infrastructure and lives\n• Agricultural productivity affected in already vulnerable regions\n• Migration pressures from water-stressed areas\n• Cascading impacts on food and energy security\n• Existing inequalities amplified\nConclusion: climate change is fundamentally altering the water cycle with severe implications for water security, particularly in developing countries and regions dependent on seasonal meltwater.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the extent to which the concept of "peak water" is a useful framework for understanding water insecurity.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with thorough analysis of the concept and its applications. Well-structured with detailed evidence.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic understanding.\n\nIndicative content:\nPeak water concept:\n• Peak renewable water — maximum sustainable yield from renewable sources\n• Peak non-renewable water — point of maximum extraction from fossil aquifers\n• Peak ecological water — point beyond which further human use causes unacceptable environmental damage\n• Analogous to peak oil — useful for framing finite resource debate\nArguments for usefulness:\n• Highlights that water resources are not limitless\n• Draws attention to non-renewable groundwater depletion\n• Useful for policy-makers in understanding sustainability limits\n• Encourages demand management and efficiency\n• Different types help distinguish between different scarcity issues\nArguments against:\n• Water is a renewable resource in most contexts — unlike oil\n• Technology (desalination, recycling) can expand effective supply\n• Oversimplifies complex local and regional variations\n• May create unnecessary alarm or fatalism\n• Does not account for governance and management improvements\n• Distribution and access matter more than absolute quantity\nCase studies:\n• Ogallala Aquifer — peak non-renewable example\n• Aral Sea — peak ecological example\n• California — multiple dimensions of peak water\nConclusion should evaluate whether the framework is genuinely useful for policy or whether it oversimplifies — likely useful as a communication tool but needs nuance in application.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the role of different stakeholders in managing water resources sustainably.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation of multiple stakeholder roles with detailed examples. Considers conflicts and synergies between stakeholders.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nGovernments:\n• Set policy frameworks, regulations and water pricing\n• Invest in infrastructure — dams, treatment plants, distribution\n• Enforce pollution controls and abstraction limits\n• Balance competing demands between sectors\n• Quality varies hugely between countries\nInternational organisations:\n• UN, World Bank provide funding and frameworks\n• Set targets e.g. SDGs\n• Facilitate transboundary cooperation\n• Technical assistance and capacity building\nPrivate sector:\n• Water companies manage supply and treatment\n• Privatisation debate — efficiency vs equity\n• Agricultural businesses as major users\n• Technology companies developing solutions\nCommunities and NGOs:\n• Community-based water management\n• Local knowledge and traditional practices\n• NGOs fill gaps where governance is weak\n• Advocacy and awareness raising\nIndividuals:\n• Consumer behaviour and water footprint\n• Willingness to pay for water services\n• Political pressure for better management\nConflicts and synergies:\n• Agriculture vs urban vs environmental needs\n• Upstream vs downstream interests\n• Short-term economic vs long-term sustainability\n• Public vs private management debates\nConclusion: effective water management requires coordination between all stakeholders — no single group can solve water insecurity alone. Multi-stakeholder governance approaches most promising.' },
    ],
  },

  'T4': {
    name: 'The Carbon Cycle & Energy Security',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "carbon sink".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A natural or artificial reservoir (1)\n• That absorbs and stores more carbon than it releases (1)' },
      { q: 'State two fossil fuels and where they are found.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Coal — found in sedimentary basins e.g. Appalachian, UK coalfields (1)\n• Oil/natural gas — found in porous rock beneath impermeable cap rock e.g. Middle East, North Sea (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "energy security".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The uninterrupted availability of energy sources (1)\n• At an affordable price (1)' },
      { q: 'State two ways carbon is transferred from the atmosphere to the biosphere.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Photosynthesis — plants absorb CO2 to produce glucose (1)\n• Absorption by oceans/diffusion into surface waters (1)\n• Direct air capture technology (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "energy mix".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The combination/proportion of different energy sources (1)\n• Used by a country or region to meet its energy needs (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between short-term and long-term carbon stores.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Short-term stores hold carbon for years to decades e.g. vegetation, soil, atmosphere (1)\n• Long-term stores hold carbon for millions of years e.g. fossil fuels, sedimentary rocks (1)\n• Human activity is releasing long-term stores rapidly, disrupting the balance (1)' },
      { q: 'State three processes that release carbon into the atmosphere.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Combustion of fossil fuels (1)\n• Respiration by living organisms (1)\n• Decomposition of organic matter (1)\n• Volcanic eruptions (1)\n• Deforestation/burning biomass (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "carbon flux".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The transfer/movement of carbon (1)\n• Between different stores/reservoirs in the carbon cycle (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by "energy pathway".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The route/supply chain by which energy is transported (1)\n• From the source of production to the point of consumption (1)\n• Includes pipelines, shipping routes, power grids (1)' },
      { q: 'State two consequences of rising atmospheric CO2 levels.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Enhanced greenhouse effect/global warming (1)\n• Ocean acidification as CO2 dissolves in seawater (1)\n• Changes to weather patterns/increased extreme events (1)\n• Melting of ice sheets/sea-level rise (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain the role of the oceans in the carbon cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Oceans absorb approximately 25% of atmospheric CO2 through diffusion (1)\n• Phytoplankton photosynthesis converts dissolved CO2 to organic carbon (1)\n• Biological pump — dead organisms sink, transferring carbon to deep ocean (1)\n• Marine organisms use carbon for shells (calcium carbonate) (1)\n• Deep ocean stores carbon for centuries/millennia (1)\n• Warming oceans may reduce CO2 absorption capacity (1)\n• Ocean acidification occurs as CO2 reacts with seawater (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how deforestation affects the carbon cycle.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Removes a major carbon sink — trees store carbon in biomass (1)\n• Burning of vegetation releases stored carbon as CO2 (1)\n• Decomposition of remaining organic matter releases CO2 (1)\n• Soil carbon is exposed and oxidises, releasing more CO2 (1)\n• Reduced photosynthesis means less CO2 removed from atmosphere (1)\n• Positive feedback — more CO2 leads to warming, further ecosystem disruption (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the factors that influence the energy mix of a country.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Availability of natural resources — fossil fuels, renewable potential (1)\n• Level of economic development — ability to invest in infrastructure (1)\n• Government policy — subsidies, regulations, climate commitments (1)\n• Technology and technical capacity (1)\n• Historical patterns and path dependency (1)\n• Public opinion and environmental awareness (1)\n• Geopolitical considerations — energy independence (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of weathering in the long-term carbon cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Chemical weathering of silicate rocks consumes atmospheric CO2 (1)\n• CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid which breaks down rock (1)\n• Carbon is transported in solution by rivers to the ocean (1)\n• Deposited as carbonate sediments on the ocean floor, forming sedimentary rock over millions of years (1)\n• Acts as a long-term thermostat regulating atmospheric CO2 (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the greenhouse effect and its role in maintaining Earths temperature.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Solar radiation passes through the atmosphere and heats the Earth surface (1)\n• Earth re-radiates energy as long-wave/infrared radiation (1)\n• Greenhouse gases (CO2, methane, water vapour) absorb and re-emit this radiation (1)\n• Keeps Earth approximately 33 degrees C warmer than it would be otherwise (1)\n• Enhanced greenhouse effect caused by human emissions increasing gas concentrations (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two geopolitical impacts of reliance on fossil fuel imports.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Dependence on politically unstable regions creates supply risk (1)\n• Energy can be used as political leverage e.g. Russia-Europe gas disputes (1)\n• Competition for resources can cause international tension/conflict (1)\n• Trade deficits from energy imports weaken economies (1)\n• Strategic reserves and diversification needed to reduce vulnerability (1)\nCredit development of 2 impacts (max 2 marks per impact)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of soil in the carbon cycle.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Soil organic matter stores approximately twice as much carbon as the atmosphere (1)\n• Decomposition of dead plant and animal material adds carbon to soil (1)\n• Microbial respiration releases CO2 from soil to atmosphere (1)\n• Soil type, temperature and moisture affect storage and release rates (1)\n• Permafrost soils store vast quantities of frozen organic carbon (1)' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing the main stores and fluxes in the carbon cycle.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Atmosphere store labelled with approximate CO2 concentration (1)\n• Biosphere store — vegetation and soil carbon (1)\n• Ocean store — surface and deep ocean carbon (1)\n• Lithosphere store — fossil fuels and sedimentary rocks (1)\n• Fluxes shown with arrows — photosynthesis, respiration, combustion, diffusion (1)\n• Human disruptions indicated — fossil fuel burning, deforestation (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the challenges of transitioning from fossil fuels to renewable energy.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Intermittency of renewables — wind and solar dependent on weather (1)\n• Energy storage technology still expensive and limited capacity (1)\n• Existing fossil fuel infrastructure represents huge sunk investment (1)\n• Job losses in fossil fuel industries create political resistance (1)\n• Renewable energy requires large land areas (1)\n• Grid infrastructure needs upgrading for distributed generation (1)\n• Developing countries may prioritise cheap fossil fuels for growth (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how permafrost thawing could create a positive feedback loop in climate change.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Permafrost stores vast quantities of organic carbon (estimated 1500 Gt) (1)\n• Rising temperatures cause permafrost to thaw (1)\n• Decomposition of released organic matter produces CO2 and methane (1)\n• These greenhouse gases cause further warming, which causes more thawing — positive feedback (1)\n• Methane is approximately 80x more potent than CO2 over 20 years (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of carbon capture and storage (CCS).', marks: 4, markScheme: '• CO2 captured from power stations or industrial sources before reaching the atmosphere (1)\n• Compressed and transported via pipeline or ship (1)\n• Injected into underground geological formations for long-term storage (1)\n• Potential to significantly reduce emissions from fossil fuel use (1)\n• Currently expensive and not yet deployed at large scale (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the environmental impacts of oil extraction.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Oil spills contaminate marine and terrestrial ecosystems (1)\n• Gas flaring releases CO2 and pollutants (1)\n• Habitat destruction from drilling infrastructure and access roads (1)\n• Water contamination from drilling fluids and produced water (1)\n• Air pollution from associated gas and volatile organic compounds (1)\n• Climate change from CO2 emissions when oil is burned (1)\n• E.g. Niger Delta — decades of pollution affecting communities (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the economic factors that influence fossil fuel production.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Global oil/gas prices determine profitability of extraction (1)\n• Cost of extraction varies — onshore cheaper than deep offshore (1)\n• Technology advances make previously uneconomic reserves viable (1)\n• Government subsidies and tax regimes affect production decisions (1)\n• Investment in infrastructure — pipelines, refineries, ports (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the enhanced greenhouse effect.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Human activities increasing concentration of greenhouse gases (1)\n• Primarily from burning fossil fuels, deforestation, agriculture (1)\n• CO2 levels risen from 280ppm pre-industrial to over 420ppm (1)\n• More outgoing radiation trapped, increasing global temperatures (1)\n• Distinct from the natural greenhouse effect which sustains life (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why energy consumption patterns vary between developed and developing countries.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Developed countries have higher per capita consumption due to lifestyle and industry (1)\n• Developing countries may rely on biomass/traditional fuels (1)\n• Industrialisation increases energy demand rapidly (1)\n• Transport sector larger in developed countries (1)\n• Energy efficiency tends to be lower in developing countries (1)\n• Climate affects heating/cooling demand (1)\n• However, rapidly industrialising countries like China now have very high total consumption (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which human activity has disrupted the carbon cycle.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific data and examples. Considers multiple aspects of disruption.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Fossil fuel burning releasing 36+ Gt CO2 per year\n• Atmospheric CO2 risen from 280 to over 420 ppm since pre-industrial era\n• Deforestation releasing stored carbon and reducing sink capacity\n• Land use change altering soil carbon stores\n• Ocean absorption increasing but causing acidification\n• Positive feedbacks amplifying disruption — permafrost, ice-albedo\n• Rate of change unprecedented in geological record\n• Carbon cycle was roughly balanced for millennia before industrialisation\n• Some natural processes still dwarf human emissions (volcanic, ocean exchange)\n• But the net imbalance is anthropogenic\n• Consequences: warming, sea-level rise, ecosystem disruption' },
      { q: 'Assess the potential of renewable energy to achieve global energy security.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment considering potential and limitations with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about renewable energy.\n\nIndicative content:\nPotential:\n• Solar and wind costs have fallen dramatically — now cheapest new electricity in many regions\n• Reduces dependence on imported fossil fuels\n• Distributed generation increases resilience\n• Growing rapidly — renewables account for increasing share of global energy\n• Technology improvements in efficiency and storage\n• Creates new jobs and industries\nLimitations:\n• Intermittency requires backup or storage solutions\n• Battery technology still expensive and resource-intensive\n• Some regions have limited renewable potential\n• Grid infrastructure needs major investment\n• Raw material supply chains (lithium, cobalt, rare earths) create new dependencies\n• Transition period requires continued fossil fuel use\n• Developing countries may lack capital for investment\nConclusion: renewables essential for future energy security but transition complex and will take decades — energy mix approach most realistic.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of international agreements in addressing climate change through carbon management.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of agreements with evaluation of effectiveness.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic awareness of agreements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Kyoto Protocol 1997 — binding targets for developed nations but limited participation\n• Paris Agreement 2015 — near-universal participation, 1.5/2 degree C target\n• COP meetings provide regular review and ratcheting mechanism\n• Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) allow country-specific approaches\n• Carbon trading mechanisms e.g. EU ETS\n• Technology transfer provisions for developing countries\n• However, current pledges insufficient to meet Paris targets\n• Enforcement mechanisms weak — voluntary compliance\n• US withdrawal under Trump weakened commitment\n• Developing countries argue for historical responsibility and climate justice\n• Fossil fuel lobbying and political obstacles\n• Some progress — global awareness and renewable investment increased' },
      { q: 'Assess the impact of the growing demand for energy on the environment.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of multiple environmental impacts with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Fossil fuel combustion — CO2 emissions, air pollution, acid rain\n• Oil extraction — spills, habitat destruction, water contamination\n• Coal mining — landscape scarring, water pollution, subsidence\n• Fracking — water contamination, induced seismicity, methane leaks\n• Nuclear — waste disposal, accident risk, thermal pollution\n• Hydroelectric — habitat flooding, sediment disruption, methane from reservoirs\n• Renewables — visual impact, land use, bird strikes (wind), material mining\n• Biomass — deforestation, food vs fuel competition\n• Overall: fossil fuels have greatest environmental impact but all sources have trade-offs\n• Growing demand means environmental impacts will increase without transition to cleaner sources' },
      { q: 'Assess the importance of the carbon cycle in regulating Earths climate.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment demonstrating understanding of feedbacks and regulation mechanisms.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Carbon cycle controls atmospheric CO2 concentration — key greenhouse gas\n• Natural fluxes between atmosphere, oceans, biosphere and lithosphere maintain balance\n• Long-term weathering thermostat — higher CO2 increases weathering which draws down CO2\n• Ocean absorption acts as buffer against rapid changes\n• Vegetation acts as carbon sink through photosynthesis\n• Geological carbon cycle operates over millions of years\n• Volcanic outgassing returns carbon from lithosphere to atmosphere\n• Without carbon cycle regulation, Earth would be much hotter or colder\n• Human disruption of cycle is overwhelming natural regulation\n• Feedbacks (positive and negative) make system complex and potentially unstable' },
      { q: 'Assess the significance of unconventional fossil fuel sources such as shale gas and tar sands.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment weighing benefits and drawbacks with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Shale gas — extracted by hydraulic fracturing, transformed US energy landscape\n• Tar sands — vast reserves in Alberta, Canada\n• Increased energy security by reducing import dependence\n• Created economic growth and employment\n• However, higher environmental costs than conventional extraction\n• Fracking linked to water contamination and induced earthquakes\n• Tar sand extraction requires huge energy input and water use\n• Higher carbon intensity than conventional fossil fuels\n• Risk of stranded assets as world transitions to low-carbon\n• Distracts from renewable energy investment\n• Political debate between economic benefits and environmental costs\n• May extend fossil fuel era when transition is needed' },
      { q: 'Assess the potential of carbon capture technologies to mitigate climate change.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment of different CCS/CDR technologies with evaluation of potential.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• CCS at point sources (power stations, cement plants) captures 85-95% of emissions\n• Direct Air Capture (DAC) removes CO2 directly from atmosphere\n• Bioenergy with CCS (BECCS) could achieve negative emissions\n• Enhanced weathering accelerates natural CO2 drawdown\n• Most climate models require some CCS/CDR to meet Paris targets\n• However, CCS currently expensive — $50-100+ per tonne CO2\n• Very few large-scale operational projects worldwide\n• Storage permanence and leakage risks\n• Energy penalty — CCS reduces power station efficiency by 25-40%\n• Risk of moral hazard — justifying continued fossil fuel use\n• May distract from proven solutions (renewables, efficiency)\n• Scale needed is enormous — billions of tonnes per year' },
      { q: 'Assess the geopolitical consequences of the global distribution of fossil fuel resources.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific geopolitical examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic awareness.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Middle East holds largest oil reserves — OPEC controls supply and pricing\n• Russia uses gas exports as political leverage over Europe\n• US shale revolution reduced import dependence, shifting geopolitical balance\n• China\'s coal dependency drives domestic and international energy policy\n• Resource curse — oil wealth can fuel corruption and conflict e.g. Nigeria, Venezuela\n• Competition for Arctic resources as ice melts\n• South China Sea tensions partly driven by energy resource claims\n• Energy pathways through politically sensitive regions (Strait of Hormuz, Suez)\n• Sanctions and trade restrictions used as geopolitical tools\n• Transition to renewables may shift geopolitical power away from fossil fuel exporters\n• New resource dependencies (lithium, cobalt) creating new geopolitical dynamics' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that nuclear energy is essential for achieving energy security and carbon reduction.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment weighing benefits and risks with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nBenefits:\n• Low-carbon electricity generation — near-zero operational emissions\n• High capacity factor — reliable baseload power\n• Energy-dense — small land footprint compared to renewables\n• Reduces dependence on imported fossil fuels\n• France generates ~70% of electricity from nuclear with low emissions\nDrawbacks:\n• Very high capital costs and long construction times\n• Radioactive waste management unresolved for millennia\n• Accident risk — Chernobyl 1986, Fukushima 2011\n• Nuclear proliferation concerns\n• Public opposition in many countries\n• Uranium supply is finite though abundant\n• Decommissioning costs substantial\n• Renewables now cheaper in many contexts\nConclusion: nuclear has a role but is not the only solution — most scenarios include a mix of nuclear, renewables and efficiency measures.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of feedback mechanisms in the carbon cycle.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment explaining both positive and negative feedbacks with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nPositive feedbacks (amplifying change):\n• Permafrost thaw releases methane and CO2 causing more warming\n• Ice-albedo effect — melting ice reduces reflectivity, absorbing more heat\n• Warmer oceans absorb less CO2, increasing atmospheric concentration\n• Forest dieback (e.g. Amazon) reduces sink capacity\n• Water vapour feedback — warmer air holds more water vapour (also a greenhouse gas)\nNegative feedbacks (stabilising):\n• Enhanced CO2 fertilisation — more CO2 increases plant growth and uptake\n• Increased weathering rates at higher temperatures draw down CO2\n• Cloud formation may increase albedo (uncertain)\nAssessment:\n• Currently positive feedbacks appear to be dominating\n• Tipping points may trigger irreversible change\n• Negative feedbacks operate over longer timescales\n• Net effect is acceleration of warming beyond direct human emissions' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the statement: "Fossil fuels remain essential for global economic development despite their environmental costs."', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with balanced argument and specific evidence. Nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nFossil fuels essential:\n• Provide approximately 80% of global primary energy\n• Critical for transport, industry, heating\n• Developing countries need cheap energy for industrialisation\n• No current alternative for some uses (aviation, heavy industry)\n• Sudden removal would cause economic collapse\n• Energy poverty affects billions — fossil fuels are accessible\nAlternatives emerging:\n• Renewable energy costs falling rapidly\n• Electric vehicles replacing internal combustion engines\n• Green hydrogen potential for hard-to-decarbonise sectors\n• Climate change costs may exceed economic benefits of fossil fuels\n• Stranded asset risk for fossil fuel investments\n• Clean energy creates new economic opportunities\n• Health costs of air pollution from fossil fuels are enormous\nConclusion: fossil fuels remain important in the short-medium term but the transition must accelerate — the economic case for renewables is increasingly compelling.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of strategies to reduce carbon emissions at different scales.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation across multiple scales with detailed examples. Well-structured with nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples across scales.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nGlobal scale:\n• Paris Agreement and COP process\n• Carbon trading schemes e.g. EU ETS\n• Technology transfer mechanisms\n• Effective at raising awareness but enforcement weak\nNational scale:\n• Carbon taxes e.g. Sweden, Canada\n• Renewable energy subsidies and targets\n• Emissions regulations and standards\n• Phase-out of coal e.g. UK, Germany\n• National policies vary greatly in ambition and effectiveness\nLocal/community scale:\n• Sustainable transport initiatives\n• Community energy schemes\n• Green building standards\n• Waste reduction and recycling\n• Urban planning and green infrastructure\nIndividual scale:\n• Diet change — reducing meat consumption\n• Transport choices — cycling, public transport\n• Energy efficiency in homes\n• Consumer choices and awareness\nEvaluation should consider that action is needed at all scales — international frameworks set direction, national policy enables change, local action implements it, and individual behaviour drives demand.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that climate change is the most significant consequence of human disruption of the carbon cycle.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Balanced evaluation comparing climate change with other consequences. Nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nClimate change as most significant:\n• Global temperature rise of 1.1+ degrees C already\n• Sea-level rise threatening coastal populations\n• Extreme weather events increasing in frequency and intensity\n• Ecosystem disruption and biodiversity loss\n• Food security threatened by changing growing conditions\n• Potential tipping points with irreversible consequences\n• Affects all regions and all sectors of society\nOther consequences:\n• Ocean acidification — threat to marine ecosystems, coral reefs, shellfish\n• Air pollution from fossil fuel combustion — millions of premature deaths annually\n• Resource depletion — finite fossil fuel reserves being exhausted\n• Geopolitical instability from resource competition\n• Environmental degradation from extraction activities\n• Health impacts of pollution beyond climate\nConclusion: climate change is arguably the most far-reaching consequence due to its global scale and cascading effects, but other consequences are also severe and interconnected.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the challenges and opportunities of transitioning to a low-carbon economy.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with detailed analysis of challenges and opportunities. Well-structured with wide-ranging evidence.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nChallenges:\n• Scale of infrastructure transformation required\n• Fossil fuel industry political and economic power\n• Job losses in traditional energy sectors\n• Intermittency and storage issues for renewables\n• Capital costs of new technology\n• Developing country energy needs and climate justice\n• Path dependency and technological lock-in\n• Consumer behaviour change required\n• Supply chain issues for critical minerals\n• Political short-termism vs long-term planning\nOpportunities:\n• New industries and job creation in clean energy\n• Improved air quality and public health\n• Energy independence from domestic renewables\n• Innovation and technological leadership\n• Reduced fuel costs over time\n• Climate change mitigation avoiding future costs\n• Circular economy approaches\n• Green finance and investment opportunities\nCase studies:\n• Denmark — wind energy leadership\n• China — largest renewable investor but also largest emitter\n• Costa Rica — near 100% renewable electricity\n• Germany — Energiewende challenges\n• Norway — oil wealth funding renewable transition\nConclusion should recognise that the transition is both necessary and achievable but requires unprecedented international cooperation, investment and political will.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the relative importance of natural and human factors in determining changes in atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed analysis of natural and human factors across timescales. Well-evidenced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nNatural factors:\n• Volcanic eruptions release CO2 (approximately 0.3 Gt/year)\n• Ocean-atmosphere CO2 exchange — temperature-dependent solubility\n• Biological productivity — photosynthesis and respiration\n• Milankovitch cycles drive glacial-interglacial CO2 changes (180-280 ppm)\n• Weathering thermostat operates over millions of years\n• Natural carbon cycle was roughly balanced pre-industrially\n• Ocean circulation changes affect CO2 distribution\nHuman factors:\n• Fossil fuel combustion — 36+ Gt CO2/year\n• Deforestation — approximately 4-5 Gt CO2/year\n• Cement production — approximately 2.5 Gt CO2/year\n• Agriculture — methane and N2O emissions\n• Land use change altering carbon stores\n• CO2 levels risen from 280 to 420+ ppm in 200 years\n• Rate of change unprecedented in geological record\nTimescale analysis:\n• Over geological time — natural factors dominant (volcanic activity, weathering, orbital cycles)\n• Over the last 200 years — human activity dominant\n• Keeling Curve provides clear evidence of anthropogenic increase\n• Ice core data shows current levels unprecedented in 800,000 years\nConclusion: while natural factors controlled CO2 levels throughout Earth history, human activity is now the dominant driver of change, overwhelming natural regulation mechanisms at a speed that natural feedbacks cannot compensate for.' },
    ],
  },

  'T5': {
    name: 'Globalisation',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "globalisation".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The growing interconnection/interdependence of the worlds economies, cultures and populations (1)\n• Through cross-border trade, investment, migration, technology and cultural exchange (1)' },
      { q: 'State two factors that have accelerated globalisation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Development of internet and communications technology (1)\n• Containerisation reducing transport costs (1)\n• Trade liberalisation/removal of tariffs (1)\n• Growth of transnational corporations (1)\n• Deregulation of financial markets (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "transnational corporation" (TNC).', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A company that operates in more than one country (1)\n• Typically with headquarters in one country and production/operations in others (1)' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a global hub city.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Major financial/business centre (1)\n• Well-connected transport infrastructure e.g. international airport (1)\n• Culturally diverse population (1)\n• Headquarters of TNCs and international organisations (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "foreign direct investment" (FDI).', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Investment by a company or individual in one country (1)\n• Into business interests/assets in another country (1)' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which globalisation has affected culture.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Spread of Western/American culture — food, music, film, fashion (1)\n• Cultural hybridisation — mixing of different cultures (1)\n• Loss of traditional/indigenous cultures (1)\n• Increased cultural awareness through media and travel (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "outsourcing".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The practice of a company contracting work/services (1)\n• To an external provider, often in another country where costs are lower (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by "time-space compression".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The reduction in time it takes to travel or communicate between places (1)\n• Due to developments in transport and communications technology (1)\n• Makes the world feel smaller and more connected (1)' },
      { q: 'State two negative impacts of globalisation on the environment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Increased carbon emissions from transport/shipping (1)\n• Deforestation for commercial agriculture e.g. palm oil, soy (1)\n• Pollution from industrialisation in developing countries (1)\n• Overconsumption of natural resources (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "Special Economic Zone" (SEZ).', marks: 3, markScheme: '• A designated area within a country (1)\n• With different economic regulations/incentives to the rest of the country (1)\n• To attract foreign investment e.g. tax breaks, relaxed regulations (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain the role of technology in driving globalisation.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Internet enables instant global communication and e-commerce (1)\n• Containerisation standardised shipping, reducing costs by 90%+ (1)\n• Jet aircraft made long-distance travel accessible and affordable (1)\n• Mobile phones connected billions in developing countries to global economy (1)\n• Social media platforms enable cultural exchange and marketing worldwide (1)\n• Financial technology enables instant international money transfers (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how TNCs contribute to economic development in host countries.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Create employment and reduce unemployment (1)\n• Transfer technology and skills to local workforce (1)\n• Increase tax revenue for host government (1)\n• Improve infrastructure — roads, utilities, communications (1)\n• Create multiplier effects — supply chains and consumer spending boost local economy (1)\n• However, profits may be repatriated to home country rather than reinvested locally (1)\n• Working conditions may be poor and wages low (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the global shift in manufacturing.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Movement of manufacturing from developed to developing/emerging economies (1)\n• Driven by lower labour costs in countries like China, India, Vietnam, Bangladesh (1)\n• TNCs seeking to maximise profits through cheaper production (1)\n• Enabled by improved transport and communications (1)\n• Countries like China became the "workshop of the world" (1)\n• Led to deindustrialisation in developed countries (1)\n• Some recent reshoring as labour costs rise and automation improves (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the social impacts of globalisation on developing countries.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Rising living standards and poverty reduction for some (1)\n• Improved access to education and healthcare (1)\n• Growing middle class with consumer aspirations (1)\n• Rural-urban migration as people seek factory employment (1)\n• Exploitation of workers — long hours, low pay, poor conditions (1)\n• Widening inequality between those connected to global economy and those excluded (1)\n• Loss of traditional livelihoods and cultural identity (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how trade blocs promote globalisation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Remove/reduce tariffs and trade barriers between member states (1)\n• Increase trade volume and economic integration (1)\n• Create larger markets attracting TNC investment (1)\n• Standardise regulations facilitating cross-border business (1)\n• Examples: EU, ASEAN, USMCA, African Union (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of international organisations in promoting globalisation.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• World Trade Organisation (WTO) promotes free trade and resolves disputes (1)\n• International Monetary Fund (IMF) provides financial stability and loans (1)\n• World Bank funds development projects in poorer countries (1)\n• These organisations promote trade liberalisation and market opening (1)\n• Structural Adjustment Programmes required deregulation and privatisation (1)\n• Criticised for promoting Western economic model and benefiting wealthy nations (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the environmental consequences of globalisation.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Increased greenhouse gas emissions from international transport (1)\n• Industrial pollution in countries with weak environmental regulations (1)\n• Deforestation for export agriculture e.g. palm oil, beef (1)\n• Overfishing of global fish stocks (1)\n• E-waste dumped in developing countries (1)\n• However, globalisation also spreads environmental awareness and technology (1)\n• International environmental agreements enabled by global cooperation (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why some countries have benefited more from globalisation than others.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Countries with educated workforce attract higher-value investment (1)\n• Good governance and political stability attract FDI (1)\n• Strategic location and transport infrastructure enable trade (1)\n• Natural resources can attract investment but may cause resource curse (1)\n• Countries that opened markets early gained first-mover advantage e.g. Asian Tigers (1)\n• Least Developed Countries often lack infrastructure and skills to participate (1)\n• Historical colonial legacies affect current economic position (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "race to the bottom" in globalisation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Countries compete to attract TNC investment (1)\n• By lowering wages, taxes, and environmental/labour regulations (1)\n• Creates downward pressure on working conditions and environmental standards (1)\n• Benefits TNCs who exploit the competition between countries (1)\n• Some argue it is overstated — companies also value stability, skills and infrastructure (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how migration is both a cause and consequence of globalisation.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Consequence: economic opportunities abroad attract labour migration (1)\n• Consequence: communication technology makes migrants aware of opportunities (1)\n• Consequence: cheaper transport enables movement (1)\n• Cause: migrants create cultural and economic connections between countries (1)\n• Cause: remittances transfer money across borders — major financial flow (1)\n• Cause: diaspora communities facilitate trade and investment networks (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of glocalisation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• The adaptation of global products or ideas to fit local cultures and markets (1)\n• TNCs modify products to suit local tastes e.g. McDonalds menus vary by country (1)\n• Balances global standardisation with local differentiation (1)\n• Recognises that pure cultural homogenisation does not occur — cultures adapt and resist (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of global supply chains in the modern economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Products assembled from components manufactured in multiple countries (1)\n• Takes advantage of comparative advantage and cost differences between locations (1)\n• Coordinated by TNCs using advanced logistics and communications (1)\n• Creates interdependence but also vulnerability to disruption (1)\n• COVID-19 pandemic exposed fragility of global supply chains (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the growth and significance of the BRICS nations in globalisation.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• BRICS = Brazil, Russia, India, China, South Africa (1)\n• Represent large emerging economies with significant global influence (1)\n• Shift in economic power away from traditional Western dominance (1)\n• China became worlds largest manufacturing economy (1)\n• India is a major services/IT outsourcing destination (1)\n• Challenge existing international institutions and power structures (1)\n• However, internal challenges remain — inequality, governance, environmental degradation (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the impact of containerisation on globalisation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Standardised containers allow seamless transfer between ship, rail and road (1)\n• Dramatically reduced shipping costs — by an estimated 90%+ (1)\n• Increased speed and efficiency of global trade (1)\n• Enabled the global shift in manufacturing by making distant production economically viable (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain two social consequences of deindustrialisation in developed countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Unemployment and loss of traditional skilled jobs (1)\n• Decline of industrial towns and communities e.g. Detroit, former UK mining towns (1)\n• Increased social deprivation and health problems (1)\n• Widening regional inequality within countries (1)\n• Loss of community identity associated with traditional industries (1)\nCredit development of 2 consequences (max 2 marks per consequence)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which globalisation has reduced global inequality.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific evidence. Considers different dimensions of inequality.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nReduced inequality:\n• Global extreme poverty fallen from 36% (1990) to under 10%\n• Hundreds of millions lifted out of poverty in China and India\n• Access to technology, healthcare and education improved globally\n• Growing middle class in emerging economies\n• Inter-country inequality reduced as emerging economies grow\nIncreased inequality:\n• Intra-country inequality rising in many nations\n• Benefits concentrated in urban areas and connected populations\n• Least Developed Countries often left behind\n• TNC profits flow to shareholders in developed countries\n• Informal/precarious employment growing\n• Gender inequality persists in many globalised workplaces\n• Environmental costs fall disproportionately on developing countries\nConclusion: globalisation has reduced some measures of global inequality while increasing others — the picture is complex and context-dependent.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of TNCs in shaping patterns of globalisation.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of TNC influence with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about TNCs.\n\nIndicative content:\n• TNCs are primary drivers of FDI flows\n• Control global supply chains and production networks\n• Apple, Samsung, Toyota etc. coordinate production across multiple countries\n• TNC decisions on investment location shape economic geography\n• Marketing and branding drive cultural globalisation\n• Lobbying influences trade policy and deregulation\n• Largest TNCs have revenues exceeding GDP of many countries\n• Tax avoidance strategies undermine host country revenues\n• However, TNCs also respond to government policies and market conditions\n• States still set rules through regulation and trade agreements\n• Consumer movements can influence TNC behaviour\n• Technology companies (Google, Amazon, Meta) now among most powerful TNCs' },
      { q: 'Assess the costs and benefits of globalisation for one named developing country.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment with specific evidence for a named country. Balanced consideration of costs and benefits.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with reference to a country.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content (example: India):\nBenefits:\n• IT and services outsourcing sector created millions of skilled jobs\n• GDP growth averaged 6-7% for decades\n• Bangalore, Hyderabad became global tech hubs\n• Growing middle class of 300+ million\n• Improved infrastructure and connectivity\n• Remittances from diaspora significant source of income\nCosts:\n• Rising inequality — urban vs rural, skilled vs unskilled\n• Agricultural sector under pressure from global competition\n• Environmental degradation from rapid industrialisation\n• Exploitation of workers in garment and manufacturing sectors\n• Cultural tensions between globalised elite and traditional communities\n• Many still in poverty despite national growth\nCredit any well-supported developing country example.' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that globalisation leads to cultural homogenisation.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of both homogenisation and resistance.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about culture.\n\nIndicative content:\nHomogenisation:\n• Global brands — McDonalds, Coca-Cola, Starbucks everywhere\n• Hollywood, Netflix, Western media dominance\n• English as global business language\n• Western fashion and consumer culture spreading\n• Social media creating global youth culture\nResistance and diversity:\n• Glocalisation — products adapted to local markets\n• Cultural resistance movements — language preservation, traditional arts\n• Bollywood, K-pop, Japanese anime — non-Western cultural exports growing\n• Internet enables niche cultures to survive and thrive\n• Hybridisation creates new cultural forms\n• Tourism can revive traditional cultures\n• Political movements against cultural imperialism\nConclusion: some homogenisation but culture is not simply replaced — it adapts, resists and creates new hybrid forms.' },
      { q: 'Assess the impact of globalisation on one named developed country.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment with specific evidence for a named country.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content (example: UK):\nBenefits:\n• London as a global financial centre\n• Access to cheap imported consumer goods\n• Cultural diversity enriched by immigration\n• Service sector growth and high-value employment\n• Universities attract global talent and revenue\nCosts:\n• Deindustrialisation of northern industrial regions\n• Manufacturing job losses to cheaper overseas competition\n• Rising inequality between London/SE and other regions\n• Anti-globalisation sentiment contributed to Brexit vote\n• Pressure on public services from immigration\n• Loss of sovereignty concerns regarding trade agreements\n• Vulnerability to global economic shocks (2008 financial crisis)\nCredit any well-supported developed country example.' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which globalisation has created winners and losers.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific examples at different scales.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nWinners:\n• TNCs and their shareholders\n• Skilled workers in globally connected sectors\n• Consumers benefiting from cheaper goods\n• Emerging economy middle classes\n• Global hub cities\n• Countries with comparative advantage in tradeable goods/services\nLosers:\n• Manufacturing workers in developed countries\n• Small-scale farmers competing with global agribusiness\n• Communities in deindustrialised regions\n• Indigenous cultures facing erosion\n• Workers in sweatshops and exploitative conditions\n• Environments damaged by industrial expansion\n• Countries unable to compete globally\n• Argument that most people are both winners and losers to different degrees' },
      { q: 'Assess the significance of global financial flows in driving globalisation.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of financial flows with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• FDI connects national economies — over $1.5 trillion annually\n• Remittances exceed aid flows — vital for developing countries\n• Financial deregulation enabled global capital movement\n• Stock markets interconnected — crises transmit rapidly\n• Tax havens facilitate capital flight and avoidance\n• IMF/World Bank lending conditions promote market opening\n• 2008 financial crisis demonstrated risks of financial globalisation\n• Cryptocurrency and fintech creating new flows\n• However, trade and technology also drive globalisation\n• Financial flows are highly uneven — concentrated in certain countries/cities' },
      { q: 'Assess the effectiveness of anti-globalisation movements.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of movements and their impact.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Fair trade movement — growing market but still niche\n• Environmental campaigns — raised awareness but emissions still rising\n• Labour rights movements — some improvement but exploitation persists\n• Political movements — Brexit, Trump trade policies challenged free trade orthodoxy\n• Occupy Wall Street highlighted inequality\n• Anti-WTO protests (Seattle 1999) drew global attention\n• Local food and buy-local movements\n• Success in raising awareness and shifting debate\n• However, fundamental structures of global capitalism largely unchanged\n• Globalisation has continued to deepen despite opposition\n• Pandemic showed both vulnerability and resilience of global systems\n• Some argue reformed globalisation rather than anti-globalisation is needed' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that globalisation is driven by developed countries for their own benefit.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment with specific evidence.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nDriven by/for developed countries:\n• WTO, IMF, World Bank historically dominated by Western nations\n• Trade rules often favour developed country interests\n• TNCs headquartered in developed countries extract profits\n• Intellectual property rules protect developed country innovations\n• Structural Adjustment Programmes imposed Western economic model\n• Colonial legacies shape current trade patterns\nCounter-arguments:\n• Emerging economies increasingly shaping globalisation — China, India\n• BRICs challenging Western dominance\n• Asian Tigers used globalisation for rapid development\n• Technology enables developing countries to leapfrog\n• South-South trade and investment growing rapidly\n• Some developed country workers are losers from globalisation\n• Globalisation now driven by market forces as much as government policy\nConclusion: historically driven by developed countries but balance of power shifting — globalisation increasingly multi-directional.' },
      { q: 'Assess the environmental sustainability of current patterns of globalisation.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment linking globalisation to environmental impacts.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nUnsustainable patterns:\n• Carbon emissions from international transport\n• Deforestation for export agriculture\n• Overconsumption driven by cheap global goods\n• Waste exported to developing countries\n• Overfishing of international waters\n• Pollution havens — dirty industries relocate to weak regulation countries\n• Planned obsolescence and throwaway consumer culture\nSustainability potential:\n• Globalisation spreads green technology\n• International environmental agreements\n• Global awareness and activism\n• Circular economy concepts spreading\n• Renewable energy technology transfer\n• Consumer pressure on TNCs for sustainability\nAssessment: current trajectory unsustainable but globalisation also provides tools for solutions — reform rather than reversal needed.' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the costs and benefits of globalisation for people and the environment.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with balanced consideration of multiple stakeholders and environmental dimensions.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nBenefits for people:\n• Poverty reduction and rising living standards\n• Access to goods, services, information and opportunities\n• Cultural exchange and understanding\n• Medical advances shared globally\n• Economic growth and development opportunities\nCosts for people:\n• Growing inequality within and between countries\n• Worker exploitation and poor conditions\n• Cultural erosion and loss of identity\n• Job insecurity and deindustrialisation\n• Health risks from fast food, pollution\nBenefits for environment:\n• Spread of green technology and awareness\n• International environmental cooperation\n• Efficiency gains in production\nCosts for environment:\n• Carbon emissions and climate change\n• Deforestation and habitat loss\n• Pollution and waste\n• Resource depletion\n• Ecological footprint expanding\nConclusion: globalisation has brought significant benefits but these are unevenly distributed, and environmental costs threaten long-term sustainability.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the statement: "Globalisation is the most significant factor shaping the world today."', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation comparing globalisation with other factors. Well-structured with nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nGlobalisation as most significant:\n• Reshaping economies — global trade worth trillions\n• Transforming cultures — global media and communication\n• Driving migration and demographic change\n• Creating new forms of governance and power\n• Affecting all countries and all aspects of life\n• Environmental impacts on planetary scale\nOther factors:\n• Climate change — existential threat regardless of globalisation\n• Technology — driving change independently of globalisation\n• Demographics — ageing populations, urbanisation\n• Geopolitics — great power competition, conflict\n• Pandemics — COVID-19 showed limits of globalisation\n• Religious and ideological movements\n• Local and national politics often override global forces\nConclusion should recognise that globalisation is deeply intertwined with these other factors — it is both a cause and consequence of many global changes, making it difficult to isolate as a single factor.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that the costs of globalisation outweigh its benefits for developing countries.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with detailed case study evidence from developing countries.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nCosts outweigh benefits:\n• Neo-colonial exploitation — resources extracted, profits repatriated\n• Working conditions in sweatshops — Rana Plaza, Bangladesh 2013\n• Environmental degradation — pollution exported to developing countries\n• Dependency on developed country markets and TNCs\n• Loss of cultural identity and traditional livelihoods\n• Debt traps from IMF/World Bank loans\n• Brain drain of educated workers to developed countries\nBenefits outweigh costs:\n• China lifted 800 million from poverty through globalisation\n• Asian Tigers achieved rapid industrialisation\n• Access to technology, medicine and information\n• Infrastructure investment by TNCs\n• Remittances support families and communities\n• Diversified economies more resilient\n• Comparative advantage allows specialisation\nConclusion: depends on context, governance, and how globalisation is managed — some developing countries have benefited enormously while others have been exploited.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the view that globalisation is entering a new phase characterised by increasing fragmentation and deglobalisation.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with detailed evidence for and against deglobalisation. Sophisticated argument considering multiple dimensions.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nEvidence for deglobalisation:\n• Trade wars — US-China tariff disputes\n• Brexit — withdrawal from EU single market\n• Rise of nationalism and protectionism globally\n• COVID-19 exposed supply chain vulnerabilities — reshoring trends\n• Sanctions regime disrupting trade patterns\n• Technology decoupling between US and China\n• Growing scepticism about free trade in developed countries\n• Pandemic border closures\nEvidence against deglobalisation:\n• Global trade volumes continue to grow overall\n• Digital globalisation accelerating — data flows, e-commerce\n• Global supply chains adapting rather than disappearing\n• International cooperation on climate change\n• Migration continues despite political resistance\n• Financial markets remain deeply integrated\n• New trade agreements being signed e.g. RCEP\n• Technology connecting more people than ever\nNuance:\n• May be "slowbalisation" rather than deglobalisation\n• Regionalisation rather than full deglobalisation — trade blocs strengthening\n• Different dimensions moving in different directions\n• Could be temporary disruption rather than fundamental shift\nConclusion should consider that globalisation is evolving rather than reversing — the nature and geography of integration is changing, but interconnection continues to deepen in many dimensions.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the role of governments in managing the impacts of globalisation on their populations.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation of government roles across different contexts with detailed examples. Well-structured with nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nGovernment tools:\n• Trade policy — tariffs, quotas, trade agreements\n• Industrial policy — supporting strategic sectors, retraining workers\n• Social policy — welfare systems, education, healthcare\n• Regulation — labour standards, environmental protection, competition law\n• Tax policy — redistributing globalisation gains\n• Immigration policy — managing labour flows\n• Investment in infrastructure and education\nEffective government responses:\n• Scandinavian model — open economies with strong social safety nets\n• Singapore — strategic positioning as global hub\n• China — managed opening of economy over decades\n• South Korea — industrial policy supported chaebols then diversification\nLess effective responses:\n• Race to the bottom on regulations and taxes\n• Failure to support displaced workers\n• Corruption diverting globalisation gains\n• Protectionism that raises consumer prices\n• Neglecting regional inequality\nCase studies from contrasting countries showing different approaches and outcomes. Conclusion should argue that government response is critical in determining whether globalisation benefits are widely shared or concentrated among elites.' },
    ],
  },

  'T6': {
    name: 'Diverse Places',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "place".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A location with meaning and significance (1)\n• Shaped by physical characteristics, human activities and peoples perceptions (1)' },
      { q: 'State two factors that influence a persons perception of place.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Age/gender/ethnicity (1)\n• Personal experiences and memories (1)\n• Media representations (1)\n• Education/socioeconomic background (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "place profile".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A description of the characteristics of a place (1)\n• Including demographic, economic, social, cultural and environmental features (1)' },
      { q: 'State two quantitative data sources that can be used to investigate place.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Census data (1)\n• Index of Multiple Deprivation (1)\n• Employment/unemployment statistics (1)\n• Crime statistics (1)\n• House price data (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "deprivation".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A lack or deficiency (1)\n• In factors such as housing, income, employment, education, health or living environment (1)' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which rural places differ from urban places.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Lower population density (1)\n• Economy more reliant on primary industry/agriculture (1)\n• Fewer services and facilities (1)\n• Different age structure — often ageing population (1)\n• Stronger community ties/sense of place (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "gentrification".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The process of renovation and improvement of an area (1)\n• By wealthier people moving in (1)\n• Often displacing existing lower-income residents (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by an "insider" and "outsider" perspective on place.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Insider — someone who has lived experience of a place, feels belonging (1)\n• Outsider — someone observing a place without deep personal connection (1)\n• Perspectives differ because insiders have emotional attachment and local knowledge that outsiders lack (1)' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which international migration affects the character of a place.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Increases ethnic and cultural diversity (1)\n• New shops, restaurants and services cater to migrant communities (1)\n• Changes to local languages spoken (1)\n• Religious buildings and community spaces established (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "lived experience" in the context of place.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The personal, everyday experience of inhabiting a place (1)\n• Including routines, relationships, feelings and memories associated with that place (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain how economic change can alter the character of a place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Deindustrialisation leads to unemployment, dereliction and out-migration (1)\n• Service sector growth attracts different workers and changes demographics (1)\n• Regeneration schemes transform physical environment — new buildings, public spaces (1)\n• Changing employment types affect income levels and social character (1)\n• Retail changes — out-of-town centres causing high street decline (1)\n• Tourism development can change local economy and culture (1)\n• Multiplier and negative multiplier effects on local communities (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how media representations influence perceptions of places.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Film, TV and music associate places with particular images/stories (1)\n• News media may focus on crime, poverty or conflict, creating negative stereotypes (1)\n• Tourism marketing creates idealised images of places (1)\n• Social media and review sites shape visitor expectations (1)\n• Estate agent language influences housing market perceptions (1)\n• Representations may not reflect the lived experience of residents (1)\n• Can create self-fulfilling prophecies — negative image discourages investment (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the causes and impacts of gentrification on a named place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Named place required e.g. Shoreditch London, Brooklyn New York, Brixton\n• Causes: artists/young professionals attracted by cheap rents and character (1)\n• Property developers invest and renovate buildings (1)\n• New cafes, shops and amenities open (1)\n• Positive impacts: physical improvement, reduced crime, increased property values (1)\n• Negative impacts: rising rents and house prices displace existing residents (1)\n• Loss of community identity and local businesses (1)\n• Social tension between newcomers and established residents (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how demographic change can affect the character of a place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Ageing population affects service provision — more healthcare, fewer schools (1)\n• Young people leaving rural areas creates age-imbalanced communities (1)\n• Immigration increases cultural diversity — new languages, religions, foods (1)\n• Counter-urbanisation brings different social groups to rural areas (1)\n• Studentification transforms areas near universities (1)\n• Changing family structures affect housing demand and community composition (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how past and present connections shape the identity of a place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Historical connections — colonial links, industrial heritage shape culture (1)\n• Transport connections determine accessibility and economic function (1)\n• Migration links create diverse communities with international connections (1)\n• Trade connections shape local economy and employment (1)\n• Digital connectivity affects access to services and opportunities (1)\n• Cultural connections through twinning, diaspora networks (1)\n• Past connections visible in architecture, place names, cultural traditions (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "sense of place" and why it varies between individuals.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Sense of place is the subjective emotional attachment people have to a location (1)\n• Shaped by personal memories, experiences and length of residence (1)\n• Differs by age — older residents may have deeper attachment (1)\n• Differs by background — socioeconomic factors affect how places are experienced (1)\n• Can be positive (topophilia) or negative (topophobia) (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how government policies have influenced the character of places.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Planning policies determine land use and building design (1)\n• Housing policy — council estates, right to buy, affordable housing requirements (1)\n• Regeneration programmes transform deprived areas (1)\n• Enterprise zones attract business to specific locations (1)\n• Transport investment changes accessibility and economic potential (1)\n• Immigration policy affects population diversity (1)\n• Austerity/spending cuts disproportionately affect some places (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the factors that create social inequality within places.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Income inequality — wages vary between occupations and sectors (1)\n• Housing costs exclude lower-income groups from some areas (1)\n• Education quality varies between schools and areas (1)\n• Health inequalities linked to deprivation, diet and access to services (1)\n• Employment opportunities unevenly distributed (1)\n• Discrimination based on race, gender, disability (1)\n• Historical patterns of inequality become entrenched over time (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the challenges faced by declining rural places.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Out-migration of young people seeking education and employment (1)\n• Ageing population placing pressure on health and social services (1)\n• Closure of services — shops, post offices, schools, pubs (1)\n• Reduced public transport provision (1)\n• Housing affordability — second homes and retirement properties push up prices (1)\n• Agricultural mechanisation reducing employment (1)\n• Loss of community cohesion and identity (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how qualitative and quantitative data can be used together to investigate place.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Quantitative data provides measurable facts — census data, IMD scores, house prices (1)\n• Qualitative data captures feelings, perceptions and experiences — interviews, photos, diaries (1)\n• Used together they give a more complete picture of a place (1)\n• Quantitative data shows what, qualitative data explains why (1)\n• Triangulation increases reliability of findings (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how migration has changed the demographic and cultural characteristics of a named place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Named place required e.g. Tower Hamlets, Leicester, Bradford\n• Population growth from international migration (1)\n• Increased ethnic and religious diversity (1)\n• New community institutions — mosques, temples, community centres (1)\n• Diverse food culture — restaurants, specialist shops, markets (1)\n• Language diversity — multilingual signage and services (1)\n• Cultural festivals and celebrations enrich local life (1)\n• Some tensions around integration and cultural change (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "placelessness" and provide examples.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Placelessness describes locations that lack distinctive character or identity (1)\n• Often caused by standardised global brands and architecture (1)\n• Examples: chain retail parks, international airports, motorway service stations (1)\n• Geographer Edward Relph argued modern development creates placelessness (1)\n• Clone towns where high streets look identical across the country (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the factors that attract people to live in urban places.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Employment opportunities — diversity of jobs in services, industry, creative sectors (1)\n• Access to services — healthcare, education, entertainment, shopping (1)\n• Social and cultural attractions — diversity, nightlife, arts (1)\n• Transport connections — public transport, proximity to workplace (1)\n• Housing availability in some areas (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how regeneration can change the character of a place.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Physical transformation — new buildings, public spaces, improved infrastructure (1)\n• Economic change — new businesses, employment opportunities, rising property values (1)\n• Social change — new residents, changing demographics and income levels (1)\n• Cultural change — arts and creative industries, new identity for area (1)\n• Environmental improvements — green spaces, reduced pollution (1)\n• However, may displace existing communities and erase heritage (1)\n• Example: London Docklands, Salford Quays, Liverpool One (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the differences between urban and rural places in terms of socioeconomic characteristics.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Urban areas have more diverse employment in services, industry and creative sectors (1)\n• Rural areas more reliant on agriculture, tourism and small businesses (1)\n• Income levels may differ — rural poverty often hidden behind pleasant landscapes (1)\n• Access to services differs significantly — rural areas have fewer facilities (1)\n• Demographics differ — rural areas often have older populations (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which globalisation has changed the character of a named place.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of globalisation impacts on a specific named place.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with reference to a place.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Named place required\n• International migration changing demographics and culture\n• TNC investment creating new employment and changing economy\n• Global brands replacing independent local shops\n• Technology connecting residents to global networks\n• International tourism shaping local economy and identity\n• However, local character and traditions persist\n• Resistance to change from some residents\n• Globalisation experienced differently by different social groups\n• Physical landscape still shapes place character regardless of globalisation\n• Balance between global influences and local distinctiveness' },
      { q: 'Assess the factors that influence the demographic characteristics of a named place.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment of multiple demographic factors with specific evidence from a named place.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with reference to a place.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Named place required\n• Migration — international and internal migration patterns\n• Economic opportunities — employment attracting or repelling specific age groups\n• Housing market — affordability affecting who can live there\n• Education — universities attract young people\n• Historical factors — past industries, settlement patterns\n• Government policy — housing, planning, immigration\n• Physical geography — coastal retirement areas, remote areas\n• Natural population change — birth and death rates\n• Specific data from census or other sources for the named place\n• Interaction between factors — e.g. economic decline causes out-migration causing ageing population' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that the character of places is increasingly shaped by external forces rather than local factors.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of external and local influences.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nExternal forces:\n• Globalisation — TNCs, international migration, global culture\n• Government policy — national planning, economic policy, austerity\n• Technology — internet, social media homogenising culture\n• Media representations shaping perception and investment\n• Climate change affecting physical environments\nLocal factors:\n• Physical geography — landscape, climate still fundamental\n• Local history and heritage\n• Community action and grassroots movements\n• Local governance and planning decisions\n• Social networks and neighbourhood relationships\n• Local economic specialisms and traditions\nConclusion: external forces increasingly influential but local factors continue to differentiate places — the interaction between external and local is what creates unique place character.' },
      { q: 'Assess the social and economic impacts of deprivation in a named place.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Detailed assessment with specific evidence from a named place.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with reference to a place.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about deprivation.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Named place required — specific IMD or equivalent data\nSocial impacts:\n• Lower life expectancy and poorer health outcomes\n• Higher crime rates and anti-social behaviour\n• Educational underachievement\n• Social isolation and mental health issues\n• Substance abuse problems\n• Weak community cohesion\nEconomic impacts:\n• High unemployment and economic inactivity\n• Low wages and insecure employment\n• Poor housing quality and overcrowding\n• Limited access to financial services\n• Negative multiplier effects — businesses close\n• Low property values\n• Cycle of deprivation — difficult to break without intervention\n• Specific data and examples from the named place' },
      { q: 'Assess the challenges of creating sustainable communities in urban areas.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of challenges with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Housing affordability — gentrification displaces existing residents\n• Balancing economic development with environmental protection\n• Transport — reducing car dependence while maintaining accessibility\n• Social cohesion — integrating diverse communities\n• Green space provision in high-density areas\n• Energy efficiency in existing building stock\n• Waste management and recycling\n• Air quality improvement\n• Inequality — ensuring benefits shared across all communities\n• Funding constraints and competing priorities\n• Political short-termism vs long-term sustainability planning\n• Community engagement in decision-making\n• Examples: eco-towns, sustainable urban extensions, retrofitting programmes' },
      { q: 'Assess the importance of the built environment in shaping the identity of a place.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific examples of how buildings shape identity.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Iconic buildings create distinctive identity e.g. Sage Gateshead, Guggenheim Bilbao\n• Architectural style reflects historical periods and cultural values\n• Industrial heritage defines former manufacturing towns\n• Religious buildings indicate cultural/religious character\n• Housing types reflect social history — terraces, council estates, suburbs\n• Street layout and public spaces shape social interaction\n• Heritage conservation preserves identity vs modernisation\n• However, identity also shaped by people, culture, economy, not just buildings\n• Same buildings experienced differently by different people\n• New development can erase or celebrate local identity' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which places have become more or less diverse over time.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with historical perspective and specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nMore diverse:\n• Post-war immigration to UK cities from Commonwealth countries\n• EU freedom of movement increased European migration\n• Globalisation of culture — food, music, media\n• Social change — greater acceptance of different lifestyles\n• Specific examples of places becoming more diverse\nLess diverse in some ways:\n• Gentrification reducing social mix in some areas\n• Residential segregation persists or increases\n• Gated communities excluding social groups\n• Rural areas becoming less economically diverse\n• Suburbanisation creating homogeneous residential areas\nNuance:\n• Diversity varies by dimension — ethnic, economic, age, cultural\n• Different places experiencing different trends\n• Policy and individual choice both shape diversity patterns\n• Diversity can coexist with inequality' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of community groups in shaping the character of places.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of community action.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Community groups resist unwanted development\n• Neighbourhood watch and community safety initiatives\n• Local history and heritage groups preserve identity\n• Community gardens and green spaces improve environment\n• Religious communities provide social support networks\n• Campaign groups influence local planning decisions\n• Community businesses and cooperatives\n• Transition town movement and local sustainability\n• However, community capacity varies — deprived areas may lack resources\n• NIMBYism can prevent necessary development\n• Not all residents are represented by community groups\n• Power imbalances mean some voices dominate' },
      { q: 'Assess the success of regeneration in transforming a named place.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Detailed assessment with specific evidence from a named place.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with reference to a place.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about regeneration.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Named place required e.g. Stratford (Olympic), Salford Quays, Liverpool, Birmingham\nSuccesses:\n• Physical transformation — new buildings, infrastructure, public realm\n• Economic growth — new jobs, businesses, increased investment\n• Improved image and reputation attracting further investment\n• Better environmental quality\n• Cultural facilities enhancing community life\nLimitations:\n• Benefits may not reach existing deprived communities\n• Gentrification displacing original residents\n• Jobs created may be low-paid or part-time\n• Increased cost of living\n• Loss of heritage and community identity\n• Displacement of problems rather than solving them\n• Specific data comparing before and after indicators' },
      { q: 'Assess the effectiveness of using the Index of Multiple Deprivation (IMD) to measure inequality within places.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment of IMD strengths and limitations.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements about IMD.\n\nIndicative content:\nStrengths:\n• Combines multiple dimensions — income, employment, education, health, crime, housing, environment\n• Small area data (LSOA level) allows detailed spatial analysis\n• Regularly updated allowing comparison over time\n• Used by government to target resources at deprived areas\n• Standardised methodology enables comparison between areas\nLimitations:\n• Relative measure — does not show absolute deprivation levels\n• LSOA boundaries may not reflect real communities\n• Masks variation within LSOAs — pockets of wealth/poverty\n• Does not capture individual experiences or perceptions\n• May not reflect hidden deprivation in rural areas\n• Does not measure all aspects of quality of life\n• Quantitative only — needs qualitative data to explain patterns\n• Some domains may be more relevant in some places than others' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that the character of places is shaped more by external than internal forces.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with detailed evidence considering multiple types of external and internal forces.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nExternal forces:\n• Globalisation — TNCs, migration, cultural flows\n• Government policy — national planning, funding decisions, welfare reform\n• Economic cycles — recession, growth affect local economies\n• Technology — internet, automation changing employment\n• Media — representations shape perceptions and investment\n• Climate change — physical environment changing\nInternal forces:\n• Local community action and identity\n• Physical geography and natural resources\n• Local history and heritage\n• Social networks and relationships\n• Local governance and planning\n• Individual agency and everyday practices\nSpecific named examples illustrating both types of force. Conclusion should argue that the distinction is often blurred — places are shaped by the interaction between external pressures and local responses.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the social and economic consequences of rapid population change in one or more named places.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed evidence from named places. Well-structured argument.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited detail.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nNamed places required\nSocial consequences:\n• Pressure on services — schools, healthcare, housing\n• Cultural diversity enriching community life\n• Tension between communities if change is rapid\n• Language barriers creating integration challenges\n• Changing identity and sense of belonging\n• Demographic imbalances e.g. ageing rural areas\nEconomic consequences:\n• Labour supply meeting demand in growing sectors\n• Entrepreneurship and business creation\n• Competition for jobs potentially depressing wages\n• Contribution to tax revenue\n• Remittances flowing out\n• Property market effects\n• Skills gaps or surpluses\nVariation:\n• Impacts differ by type of population change (immigration, counter-urbanisation, studentification)\n• Different social groups experience change differently\n• Government response affects outcomes\n• Local context matters — economic health, existing diversity, community capacity' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of different approaches to managing social inequality within places.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation of multiple approaches with specific examples.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nGovernment approaches:\n• Regeneration schemes — improve physical environment but may cause gentrification\n• Education policy — academy schools, pupil premium targeting disadvantaged students\n• Housing policy — affordable housing requirements, council housing\n• Welfare reform — universal credit, benefits system\n• Enterprise zones — tax incentives to attract businesses\nCommunity approaches:\n• Community development trusts\n• Social enterprises and cooperatives\n• Neighbourhood planning\n• Grassroots campaigns for services\nPrivate sector:\n• Corporate social responsibility\n• Employment and training programmes\nEvaluation:\n• Regeneration often benefits incomers more than existing residents\n• Addressing symptoms vs root causes\n• Short-term funding vs long-term structural change\n• Spatial targeting vs universal provision debate\n• Need for integrated approaches combining physical, economic and social investment' },
      { q: 'Discuss the factors that create and sustain diverse communities within places.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with wide-ranging factors and detailed case study evidence. Sophisticated analysis of how diversity is created and maintained.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nFactors creating diversity:\n• International migration — historical and contemporary flows\n• Internal migration — rural-urban, counter-urbanisation, gentrification\n• Economic factors — different industries attracting different workers\n• Housing market — affordability creating social mix or segregation\n• Historical factors — settlement patterns, colonial connections\n• University towns attracting students from diverse backgrounds\nFactors sustaining diversity:\n• Community institutions — places of worship, community centres\n• Cultural events and festivals\n• Ethnic economies — specialist shops, restaurants, services\n• Social networks and family connections\n• Tolerance and integration policies\n• Mixed-use neighbourhoods and public spaces\nThreats to diversity:\n• Gentrification pricing out lower-income groups\n• Residential segregation and gated communities\n• Discrimination and prejudice\n• Economic decline reducing opportunities\n• Planning policies creating uniform developments\nCase studies from contrasting places showing different diversity patterns. Conclusion should discuss whether diversity is inherently good and how it can be maintained in the face of market forces and social change.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the extent to which places can be managed to create a sense of belonging for all residents.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed evidence from multiple contexts. Sophisticated discussion of belonging and management.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nCreating belonging:\n• Community facilities — libraries, parks, community centres as shared spaces\n• Heritage preservation connecting people to local history\n• Participatory planning involving residents in decisions\n• Public art and placemaking initiatives\n• Events and festivals celebrating local identity and diversity\n• Mixed-tenure housing creating socially mixed communities\n• Integration programmes for new migrants\n• Community organisations and volunteering\nChallenges:\n• Diversity means different groups have different needs and values\n• Gentrification undermines belonging for displaced residents\n• Some groups systematically excluded by discrimination\n• Rapid change disrupts established community bonds\n• Resources constrained by austerity and competing priorities\n• Digital divide creates uneven access to community information\n• Belonging is subjective — difficult to manage or measure\n• Power imbalances mean some voices heard more than others\nCase studies:\n• Successful community cohesion programmes\n• Failed regeneration that destroyed community\n• Areas managing diversity effectively\nConclusion should recognise that belonging cannot be fully engineered by management — it emerges from everyday lived experience and social relationships, but policy can create conditions that support or undermine it.' },
    ],
  },

  'T7': {
    name: 'Superpowers',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "superpower".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• A nation/state with dominant global influence (1)\n• Across economic, military, political and cultural dimensions (1)' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a superpower.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Large military capability including nuclear weapons (1)\n• Major economic power with global influence (1)\n• Political influence in international organisations (1)\n• Cultural/soft power influence globally (1)\n• Large geographic area and/or population (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "soft power".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The ability to influence others through attraction and persuasion (1)\n• Rather than coercion or force — includes culture, values, diplomacy (1)' },
      { q: 'State two differences between a superpower and an emerging power.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Superpowers have established global influence, emerging powers have growing regional/global influence (1)\n• Superpowers have dominant military, emerging powers may be building military capacity (1)\n• Superpowers shape international institutions, emerging powers seek greater representation (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "unipolarity".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• An international system with one dominant superpower (1)\n• That has disproportionate influence over global affairs e.g. US after Cold War (1)' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which superpowers exert influence over other countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Military intervention or threat of force (1)\n• Economic aid, trade agreements or sanctions (1)\n• Diplomatic pressure and alliance building (1)\n• Cultural influence through media, language, education (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "multipolarity".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• An international system with multiple centres of power (1)\n• No single nation dominates (1)\n• Power is distributed among several major states or blocs (1)' },
      { q: 'State two international organisations through which superpowers exert influence.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• United Nations Security Council — veto power for permanent members (1)\n• NATO — US-led military alliance (1)\n• World Bank/IMF — economic influence (1)\n• WTO — trade rule-setting (1)\n• G7/G20 — economic coordination (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the concept of "hard power".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The ability to influence others through coercion (1)\n• Using military force or economic sanctions (1)\n• Contrast with soft power which uses attraction and persuasion (1)' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why China is considered an emerging superpower.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Worlds second-largest economy/largest by PPP (1)\n• Rapidly modernising military including nuclear capability (1)\n• Growing diplomatic influence especially in Africa and Asia (1)\n• Belt and Road Initiative extending global economic reach (1)\n• Permanent member of UN Security Council (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain the factors that have contributed to the USAs superpower status.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Largest economy by nominal GDP — global financial dominance (1)\n• Most powerful military — largest defence budget, global bases (1)\n• Nuclear arsenal — deterrent capability (1)\n• Cultural influence — Hollywood, technology companies, English language (1)\n• Political influence — UN Security Council veto, leadership of NATO (1)\n• Geographic advantages — vast natural resources, strategic location (1)\n• Innovation and technology — Silicon Valley, universities (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how the British Empire demonstrated the characteristics of a superpower.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Controlled approximately 25% of worlds land area and population (1)\n• Dominant naval power — ruled the seas for centuries (1)\n• Global economic influence through trade and the City of London (1)\n• Cultural influence — English language, legal systems, education (1)\n• Political control over colonies and territories worldwide (1)\n• Industrial Revolution gave technological and economic advantage (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how Chinas Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) extends its global influence.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Infrastructure investment across Asia, Africa, Europe — roads, railways, ports (1)\n• Creates economic dependency and political influence in recipient countries (1)\n• Secures access to resources and markets for Chinese goods (1)\n• Alternative development model to Western-led institutions (1)\n• Debt-trap diplomacy concerns — countries unable to repay loans (1)\n• Expands Chinas soft power and diplomatic relationships (1)\n• Strategic military implications — port access in Indian Ocean (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of military power in maintaining superpower status.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Nuclear deterrent prevents direct attack from rival powers (1)\n• Conventional military capability enables intervention globally (1)\n• Military alliances (NATO) extend sphere of influence (1)\n• Defence industry drives technological innovation (1)\n• Military presence through overseas bases projects power globally (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "Thucydides Trap" in relation to US-China relations.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• When a rising power (China) threatens to displace an established power (USA) (1)\n• Historical pattern suggests this often leads to conflict (1)\n• Competition in trade, technology, military and influence (1)\n• However, nuclear deterrent and economic interdependence may prevent war (1)\n• Some argue the relationship is more complex than simple power transition theory suggests (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how international institutions reflect and reinforce superpower influence.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• UN Security Council — 5 permanent members with veto reflect post-WW2 power structure (1)\n• IMF/World Bank — voting shares weighted towards developed nations (1)\n• WTO rules often favour powerful trading nations (1)\n• NATO — US provides majority of military capability (1)\n• G7 excludes emerging powers from key economic decisions (1)\n• Calls for reform from BRICS and developing countries (1)\n• Institutions slow to adapt to changing power dynamics (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how economic power contributes to superpower influence.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Large GDP provides resources for military spending and global initiatives (1)\n• Trade relationships create dependency and leverage (1)\n• Control of key currencies — US dollar as global reserve currency (1)\n• TNCs headquartered in superpower project economic influence (1)\n• Foreign aid and development loans create political goodwill (1)\n• Economic sanctions used as tool of coercion (1)\n• Technology and innovation leadership maintain economic advantage (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of culture in superpower influence.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Cultural exports — films, music, fashion, food shape global preferences (1)\n• Language — English as global lingua franca is a major US/UK advantage (1)\n• Education — world-leading universities attract global elites (1)\n• Media and social media platforms spread values and lifestyle (1)\n• Soft power creates admiration and aspiration rather than resentment (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain why some nations have declined as superpowers.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Military overstretch — cost of maintaining global presence e.g. Soviet Union (1)\n• Economic decline relative to rising powers (1)\n• Loss of colonies/territories reducing global reach e.g. British Empire (1)\n• Internal political instability or revolution (1)\n• Failure to adapt to changing technology or economic conditions (1)\n• Rising competitors with larger populations and growing economies (1)\n• Ideological failure — collapse of communism weakened Soviet Union (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the tensions that can arise from changing patterns of superpower influence.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Trade disputes between established and rising powers e.g. US-China (1)\n• Arms races and military competition (1)\n• Proxy conflicts in third countries (1)\n• Competition for resources and spheres of influence (1)\n• Tensions in international institutions over representation (1)\n• Cyber warfare and technological competition (1)\n• Ideological competition — democracy vs authoritarianism (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "spheres of influence" in the context of superpower geopolitics.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Areas where a superpower has dominant political, economic or military influence (1)\n• Historically associated with Cold War division — US and Soviet spheres (1)\n• Maintained through alliances, military bases, economic ties (1)\n• Can lead to conflict when spheres overlap or are contested (1)\n• Russia considers former Soviet states as its sphere of influence (1)' },
      { q: 'Sketch a diagram showing the shift from bipolarity to multipolarity in the global power structure since 1945.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '• Bipolarity shown — USA and USSR as two dominant powers post-1945 (1)\n• Cold War context indicated — NATO vs Warsaw Pact (1)\n• 1991 collapse of USSR creating temporary unipolarity (1)\n• Current shift towards multipolarity shown (1)\n• Multiple centres of power identified — USA, China, EU, Russia, India, emerging powers (1)\n• Arrows or timeline indicating direction of change (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of natural resources in determining superpower status.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Energy resources (oil, gas) provide economic power and leverage e.g. Saudi Arabia, Russia (1)\n• Mineral resources essential for industry and technology (1)\n• Agricultural capacity supports large populations and food security (1)\n• Water resources increasingly important for future security (1)\n• However, resource wealth alone is insufficient — governance, technology and human capital also matter (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Cold War shaped the pattern of global superpowers.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Created bipolar world — USA vs USSR (1)\n• Divided the world into two competing ideological blocs — capitalism vs communism (1)\n• Nuclear arms race — Mutually Assured Destruction maintained balance (1)\n• Proxy wars in Korea, Vietnam, Afghanistan, Africa (1)\n• Space race and technology competition (1)\n• Collapse of USSR in 1991 left USA as sole superpower (1)\n• Legacy still shapes current geopolitics — NATO expansion, Russian concerns (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how India could become a future superpower.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Worlds largest population — demographic dividend with young workforce (1)\n• Rapidly growing economy — fifth largest GDP, projected to be third (1)\n• Nuclear-armed military with growing capability (1)\n• IT and services sector creating global connections (1)\n• Strategic geographic location in Indian Ocean (1)\n• However, challenges remain — poverty, inequality, infrastructure, governance (1)\n• Regional rivalries with Pakistan and China (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which the USA remains the worlds dominant superpower.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment considering multiple dimensions of power with specific evidence.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nUSA still dominant:\n• Largest military budget — more than next 10 countries combined\n• Dollar remains global reserve currency\n• Technology leadership — Silicon Valley, AI, biotech\n• Cultural influence — Hollywood, social media, English language\n• Alliance system — NATO, bilateral agreements worldwide\n• World-leading universities attracting global talent\nDecline indicators:\n• China closing economic gap — may overtake by GDP PPP\n• Domestic political polarisation weakening global leadership\n• Relative military overstretch — Afghanistan, Iraq\n• Rising multipolarity — BRICS challenging US-led institutions\n• Climate and environmental challenges\n• Debt levels rising\n• Some allies questioning reliability of US commitments\nConclusion: USA remains most powerful single nation but increasingly challenged — moving from unipolarity to a more contested international order.' },
      { q: 'Assess the challenges China faces in becoming a true superpower.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of multiple challenges with specific evidence.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Ageing population due to former one-child policy — demographic challenges\n• Income inequality between coastal cities and rural interior\n• Environmental degradation — air pollution, water scarcity, climate vulnerability\n• Political system — authoritarian governance may limit innovation and soft power\n• Territorial disputes — South China Sea, Taiwan, border tensions with India\n• Debt levels — corporate and local government debt concerns\n• Technology restrictions — US semiconductor export controls\n• Soft power limitations — less cultural appeal than USA\n• Human rights criticisms limiting international support\n• Dependency on energy imports — energy security vulnerability\n• However, BRI expanding influence, growing military, technological catch-up\n• Conclusion: significant challenges but trajectory still upward' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which the world is moving towards a multipolar order.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific evidence for and against multipolarity.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nEvidence for multipolarity:\n• China as second-largest economy with global ambitions\n• EU as major economic bloc and soft power\n• Russia reasserting regional and global influence\n• India and Brazil growing in significance\n• BRICS challenging Western-dominated institutions\n• Regional powers exerting greater independence\nEvidence against:\n• USA still militarily dominant by wide margin\n• Dollar remains global currency\n• US technology companies dominate globally\n• NATO remains strongest military alliance\n• No other nation has comparable global reach\n• China faces significant domestic challenges\nConclusion: world is in transition — not fully multipolar but no longer unipolar. Perhaps "multipolar with US primacy" best describes current situation.' },
      { q: 'Assess the importance of soft power versus hard power in the 21st century.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment comparing both types with specific contemporary examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about soft and hard power.\n\nIndicative content:\nSoft power importance:\n• Cultural influence shapes global preferences and alliances\n• Diplomacy and persuasion more effective than coercion long-term\n• International cooperation requires consent and legitimacy\n• K-pop, Bollywood showing emerging nations soft power potential\n• Development aid builds political goodwill\n• Education and language spread values\nHard power importance:\n• Military deterrence still essential for security\n• Economic sanctions remain powerful coercive tool\n• Nuclear capability underpins superpower status\n• Some situations require military intervention\n• Hard power protects interests that soft power cannot\nSmart power:\n• Concept of combining soft and hard power strategically\n• Most effective superpowers use both\n• Balance depends on context and objectives\nConclusion: both remain important but soft power increasingly significant in an interconnected world — hard power alone insufficient for lasting influence.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of international organisations in maintaining or challenging the existing power structure.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of both maintaining and challenging roles.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nMaintaining existing structure:\n• UN Security Council veto reflects 1945 power balance\n• IMF/World Bank voting shares favour Western nations\n• NATO reinforces US military leadership\n• G7 excludes major emerging economies\n• Trade rules often favour established economic powers\nChallenging existing structure:\n• BRICS New Development Bank as alternative to World Bank\n• Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB) led by China\n• G20 gives emerging powers a voice\n• Calls for UN Security Council reform growing\n• Shanghai Cooperation Organisation as alternative security framework\n• African Union asserting regional autonomy\nConclusion: international institutions both reflect and perpetuate existing power structures but face growing pressure for reform from emerging powers.' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that Russias superpower status is declining.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific evidence for and against decline.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nEvidence of decline:\n• Economy much smaller than USA or China — dependent on energy exports\n• Demographic decline — shrinking and ageing population\n• Limited soft power appeal\n• Technological lag behind USA and China\n• Economic sanctions reducing international integration\n• Military capacity diminished from Soviet era\n• Brain drain of educated professionals\nEvidence against decline:\n• Second-largest nuclear arsenal\n• UN Security Council permanent member with veto\n• Significant energy resources — leverage over Europe\n• Military intervention capability demonstrated (Syria)\n• Cyber and information warfare capabilities\n• Arctic resources and strategic positioning\n• Alliance with China on some issues\n• Historical depth of strategic experience\nConclusion: Russia is diminished from Soviet superpower status but retains significant disruptive capability — more of a "spoiler" power than a true superpower.' },
      { q: 'Assess the impacts of superpower rivalry on developing countries.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment with specific examples of impacts.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nNegative impacts:\n• Proxy wars during Cold War — Vietnam, Korea, Angola caused devastation\n• Arms sales fuel conflict in unstable regions\n• Debt from superpower loans can trap countries\n• Exploitation of resources to serve superpower interests\n• Forced alignment limiting policy independence\n• Sanctions affect civilian populations\nPositive impacts:\n• Competition for influence drives aid and investment\n• Chinas BRI providing infrastructure in Africa, Asia\n• Cold War competition funded development in allied states\n• Technology transfer from competing superpowers\n• Developing countries can play superpowers off against each other\nContemporary examples:\n• Africa as arena for US-China competition\n• Latin America — Chinese investment challenging US influence\n• Central Asia — Russian and Chinese interests overlap\nConclusion: superpower rivalry creates both opportunities and dangers for developing countries — outcomes depend on local governance and strategic positioning.' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which the EU functions as a superpower.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment considering multiple dimensions of power.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about the EU.\n\nIndicative content:\nSuperpower characteristics:\n• Worlds largest single market — huge economic weight\n• Major trading power — trade agreements worldwide\n• Regulatory superpower — EU standards adopted globally (Brussels effect)\n• Significant soft power — human rights, environmental leadership, cultural influence\n• Development aid — collectively largest aid donor\n• Diplomatic influence in international institutions\nLimitations:\n• Not a state — lacks unified foreign policy and military\n• Dependent on NATO/USA for defence\n• Internal divisions weaken unified action\n• Brexit reduced size and influence\n• Slow decision-making processes\n• Limited hard power capability\n• Demographic challenges — ageing population\n• Energy dependence on Russia (pre-2022)\nConclusion: EU is a significant global actor with superpower-level economic influence but lacks the military unity and political cohesion to be a true superpower.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of technology in determining superpower status in the 21st century.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of technology\'s role with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Artificial intelligence as key competitive frontier — US-China AI race\n• Semiconductor technology — control of chip manufacturing gives strategic advantage\n• Space technology — military and commercial applications\n• Cyber warfare capability increasingly important\n• 5G and telecommunications infrastructure — Huawei controversy\n• Quantum computing — potential to revolutionise computing and cryptography\n• Biotechnology and medical innovation\n• Social media platforms as tools of influence\n• Technology drives economic growth and military capability\n• Countries that lead in tech innovation will lead geopolitically\n• However, technology alone insufficient — needs economic base, governance, human capital\n• Risk of technological decoupling between US and China blocs' },
      { q: 'Assess the geopolitical significance of the Arctic region for superpowers.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of Arctic significance with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Vast untapped oil and gas reserves (estimated 13% of undiscovered oil, 30% of gas)\n• New shipping routes opening as ice melts — Northwest Passage, Northern Sea Route\n• Military strategic importance — submarine routes, missile detection\n• Fishing grounds expanding into previously ice-covered waters\n• Territorial claims by Russia, Canada, Denmark, Norway, USA\n• Russia most active — military build-up, resource claims, icebreaker fleet\n• China declares itself "near-Arctic state" seeking influence\n• Environmental concerns about exploitation\n• Arctic Council as governance framework but tensions rising\n• Climate change accelerating strategic importance\n• Symbolises wider superpower competition for resources and territory' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that the rise of China represents the most significant shift in global power since the end of the Cold War.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with balanced argument and specific evidence.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may lack balance.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nChinas rise as most significant:\n• Second-largest economy, projected to become largest\n• Belt and Road Initiative extending global influence across continents\n• Military modernisation — largest navy by number of vessels\n• Technology competition — AI, 5G, space programme\n• Challenging US-led international order\n• Alternative development model (state capitalism)\n• 1.4 billion people integrated into global economy\nOther shifts:\n• Collapse of USSR itself was transformative\n• Rise of terrorism/non-state actors post-9/11\n• EU integration and expansion\n• India emerging as major power\n• Rise of regional powers — Turkey, Saudi Arabia, Brazil\n• Climate change as geopolitical issue\n• Technology revolution reshaping all forms of power\nConclusion: Chinas rise is arguably the most significant state-level power shift but occurs alongside other transformative changes — the shift to multipolarity involves multiple actors and forces.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the extent to which superpower status depends on economic power rather than military power.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed examples across multiple superpowers. Well-structured with nuanced conclusion.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nEconomic power more important:\n• Economic strength funds military and all other forms of power\n• Trade relationships create more lasting influence than military threats\n• Economic sanctions increasingly effective tool of coercion\n• TNCs project influence globally through investment and trade\n• Technology companies (US) shape global digital infrastructure\n• Chinas rise primarily economic — BRI more influential than military\n• Soviet Union showed that military power without economic strength is unsustainable\nMilitary power more important:\n• Nuclear deterrent essential for security and status\n• Military capability enables intervention to protect interests\n• Russia retains influence primarily through military strength\n• US global military presence underpins alliance system\n• Arms sales create dependency and influence\n• Cyber and space military capabilities increasingly important\nBoth needed:\n• Smart power concept — combining economic and military tools\n• No successful superpower has relied on one dimension alone\n• UK as example of economic decline reducing military capacity\n• Japan and Germany show economic power without military superpower status\nConclusion: economic power is arguably the foundation but military capability remains essential for true superpower status — the balance varies by context and historical period.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the consequences of superpower actions on the global environment.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with specific examples of environmental consequences.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nNegative consequences:\n• Superpowers are largest carbon emitters — USA and China combined 40%+\n• Military activities cause environmental damage — bases, weapons testing\n• Resource extraction to fuel superpower economies\n• Industrial pollution concentrated in superpower production zones\n• Resistance to binding environmental agreements\n• Arms production and nuclear testing — long-term contamination\nPositive consequences:\n• Superpowers invest in green technology — US, China largest renewable investors\n• International leadership needed for climate agreements\n• Space technology enables environmental monitoring\n• Scientific research capacity to develop solutions\n• Economic power to fund conservation\nNuance:\n• Superpowers can both cause and solve environmental problems\n• Developing countries argue superpowers have historical responsibility\n• Climate justice debate — who should bear the costs?\nConclusion: superpowers bear disproportionate responsibility for environmental damage but also hold the keys to solutions — their choices will determine the planets environmental future.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the extent to which the concept of "superpower" remains relevant in the 21st century.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion with sophisticated analysis of how power is changing. Well-structured with detailed evidence.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nStill relevant:\n• USA and China clearly more powerful than other nations\n• Military power still concentrated in a few states\n• UN Security Council veto demonstrates formal superpower privilege\n• Great power competition returned as dominant geopolitical narrative\n• Nuclear weapons define a clear power hierarchy\n• Bilaterals like US-China shape global agenda\nLess relevant:\n• Non-state actors (TNCs, NGOs, terrorist groups) wield significant power\n• Globalisation has diffused power away from states\n• Economic interdependence means no nation truly independent\n• Transnational challenges (climate, pandemics) cannot be solved by single superpowers\n• Regional powers increasingly important — Turkey, Saudi, Nigeria\n• Cyber domain doesnt respect traditional power hierarchies\n• Soft power harder to monopolise than hard power\n• Global governance increasingly multilateral rather than superpower-led\nEvolving concept:\n• Technology creating new dimensions of power not captured by traditional definition\n• Environmental leadership as new form of influence\n• Data and information as power resources\n• Network power replacing hierarchical power\n• Concept may need redefining rather than abandoning\nConclusion should argue that the concept remains useful for understanding global politics but needs updating to account for new forms of power, non-state actors and the increasingly complex, interconnected nature of international relations.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the potential consequences of a shift from a unipolar to a multipolar world order.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation considering multiple consequences across different dimensions. Detailed evidence and sophisticated argument.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nPositive consequences:\n• More representative global governance\n• Reduced dominance of Western values and interests\n• Greater policy autonomy for smaller nations\n• Competition between powers could drive innovation\n• Multiple development models available for developing countries\n• Regional powers better placed to address local issues\n• Reduced resentment of single superpower dominance\nNegative consequences:\n• Greater instability and uncertainty\n• More potential for conflict between rival powers\n• Weaker international cooperation on global challenges\n• Arms races and military competition\n• Proxy conflicts in contested regions\n• International institutions may become gridlocked\n• Trade wars and economic fragmentation\n• Difficulty addressing global commons issues (climate, oceans)\nHistorical parallels:\n• Pre-WW1 multipolarity led to devastating conflict\n• Concert of Europe showed multipolarity can maintain peace\n• Cold War bipolarity was stable but dangerous\n• Post-Cold War unipolarity had both stability and overreach\nCase studies of current multipolar dynamics:\n• US-China competition in Indo-Pacific\n• Russia-NATO tensions in Europe\n• Regional competitions in Middle East\nConclusion should consider whether multipolarity is inherently more or less stable than unipolarity — likely depends on whether powers can establish rules and institutions to manage competition, as in any period of power transition.' },
    ],
  },

  'T8': {
    name: 'Health, Human Rights & Intervention',
    questions: [
      // 2-3 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Define the term "human development".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• The process of enlarging peoples choices and freedoms (1)\n• Including health, education and standard of living (1)' },
      { q: 'State two indicators used to measure human development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Life expectancy at birth (1)\n• Mean/expected years of schooling (1)\n• Gross National Income per capita (1)\n• Human Development Index (HDI) combines all three (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "human rights".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Fundamental rights and freedoms to which all people are entitled (1)\n• Regardless of nationality, ethnicity, gender, religion or other status (1)' },
      { q: 'State two diseases classified as non-communicable.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Cancer (1)\n• Cardiovascular disease/heart disease (1)\n• Diabetes (1)\n• Chronic respiratory disease (1)\n• Mental health disorders (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "epidemiological transition".', marks: 3, markScheme: '• The shift in the pattern of disease (1)\n• From infectious/communicable diseases to non-communicable diseases (1)\n• As a country develops economically (1)' },
      { q: 'State two social factors that affect health.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Education level — health literacy and awareness (1)\n• Income/poverty — ability to afford healthcare and nutrition (1)\n• Gender — differential access to healthcare (1)\n• Ethnicity — health inequalities between groups (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "intervention".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Action taken by external actors (states, organisations) (1)\n• To influence the internal affairs of another country, often justified by humanitarian or geopolitical reasons (1)' },
      { q: 'State two examples of direct military intervention by a superpower since 2000.', marks: 2, markScheme: '• US/UK invasion of Iraq 2003 (1)\n• NATO intervention in Libya 2011 (1)\n• US invasion of Afghanistan 2001 (1)\n• Russian intervention in Syria 2015 (1)' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between communicable and non-communicable diseases.', marks: 3, markScheme: '• Communicable diseases are infectious — can be transmitted between people (1)\n• Non-communicable diseases cannot be transmitted — caused by lifestyle, genetics, environment (1)\n• Communicable diseases more prevalent in developing countries, NCDs in developed countries (though this is changing) (1)' },
      { q: 'Define the term "geopolitical intervention".', marks: 2, markScheme: '• Actions taken by a state or alliance to influence events in another country (1)\n• Motivated by strategic, political or economic interests rather than humanitarian concerns (1)' },

      // 4-6 mark questions (15)
      { q: 'Explain the factors that influence global patterns of health and disease.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Level of economic development — determines healthcare infrastructure and spending (1)\n• Climate and environment — tropical regions face higher burden of vector-borne diseases (1)\n• Access to clean water and sanitation — diarrhoeal diseases linked to poor water (1)\n• Education — health literacy affects prevention and treatment-seeking behaviour (1)\n• Diet and lifestyle — nutrition deficiencies or obesity affect health outcomes (1)\n• Governance — quality of health policy and systems (1)\n• Conflict — disrupts healthcare systems and causes injury/displacement (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how economic development affects health outcomes.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Higher income countries can invest more in healthcare infrastructure (1)\n• Better nutrition available with higher incomes reducing malnutrition diseases (1)\n• Improved sanitation and clean water provision reduces infectious disease (1)\n• Education increases health awareness and disease prevention (1)\n• However, development brings NCDs — obesity, heart disease, diabetes (1)\n• Epidemiological transition occurs as countries develop (1)\n• Inequality within developed countries means health gaps persist (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of international organisations in promoting human rights.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• United Nations — Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1948) sets global standards (1)\n• UN Human Rights Council monitors and reports on violations (1)\n• International Criminal Court prosecutes crimes against humanity (1)\n• NGOs like Amnesty International campaign and document abuses (1)\n• Convention on the Rights of the Child — most widely ratified treaty (1)\n• However, enforcement is weak — sovereignty limits intervention (1)\n• Some states reject international oversight as interference (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the arguments for humanitarian intervention.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Responsibility to Protect (R2P) doctrine — states have duty to protect civilians (1)\n• Prevent genocide, ethnic cleansing and crimes against humanity (1)\n• International community has moral obligation when states fail to protect (1)\n• Can restore stability and prevent wider regional conflict (1)\n• Protect human rights when domestic institutions fail (1)\n• International law provides frameworks for legitimate intervention (1)\n• Examples: Kosovo 1999, Libya 2011 (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the arguments against military intervention.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Violates national sovereignty — fundamental principle of international law (1)\n• Often motivated by self-interest rather than humanitarian concerns (1)\n• Can cause more harm than good — civilian casualties, infrastructure destruction (1)\n• Regime change may create power vacuum and instability (1)\n• Selective application — not all human rights crises trigger intervention (1)\n• Colonial overtones — powerful nations imposing will on weaker ones (1)\n• Often fails to achieve lasting peace — e.g. Libya, Iraq, Afghanistan (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how gender inequality affects health in developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Women may have less access to healthcare due to cultural restrictions (1)\n• Maternal mortality high where women lack access to skilled birth attendants (1)\n• Girls education cut short, reducing health literacy and economic independence (1)\n• Gender-based violence causes physical and psychological harm (1)\n• Women doing most unpaid care work have less time for own health needs (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of NGOs in addressing global health challenges.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF) provides medical care in conflict zones and emergencies (1)\n• Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation funds research and vaccination programmes (1)\n• Red Cross provides disaster relief and health services (1)\n• NGOs fill gaps where governments lack capacity or will (1)\n• Advocacy and awareness raising on health issues (1)\n• However, NGOs have limited resources and cannot substitute for government systems (1)\n• Coordination challenges between multiple NGOs and governments (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the impact of HIV/AIDS on development in sub-Saharan Africa.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Reduced life expectancy in worst-affected countries — some dropped below 50 years (1)\n• Loss of working-age adults reduces economic productivity (1)\n• Healthcare systems overwhelmed by treatment demand (1)\n• Orphaned children — education and welfare burden (1)\n• Agricultural output declined as farmers fell ill (1)\n• Social stigma prevented treatment and prevention (1)\n• However, antiretroviral treatment programmes have improved outcomes significantly (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "development aid" and its role in improving health outcomes.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Financial and technical assistance from wealthier to poorer countries (1)\n• Can fund healthcare infrastructure, training and medicines (1)\n• Bilateral aid (government to government) and multilateral aid (through organisations) (1)\n• However, effectiveness debated — aid dependency, corruption, misallocation (1)\n• Tied aid may not address recipients actual priorities (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the factors that contribute to maternal mortality in developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Lack of access to skilled birth attendants and emergency obstetric care (1)\n• Poverty preventing access to healthcare facilities (1)\n• Distance to healthcare in rural areas (1)\n• Cultural practices restricting womens healthcare access (1)\n• Malnutrition and anaemia weakening mothers health (1)\n• Early marriage and pregnancy in young girls (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "Responsibility to Protect" (R2P).', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Adopted by UN World Summit 2005 (1)\n• States have primary responsibility to protect their populations from genocide, war crimes, ethnic cleansing, crimes against humanity (1)\n• If a state fails, the international community has responsibility to act (1)\n• Can involve diplomatic, humanitarian or as last resort military action through UN Security Council (1)\n• Controversial — sovereignty vs intervention debate (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how conflict affects health and human development.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Direct casualties — deaths and injuries from fighting (1)\n• Destruction of healthcare infrastructure — hospitals, clinics (1)\n• Displacement of populations — refugee health crises (1)\n• Food insecurity and malnutrition from disrupted agriculture (1)\n• Mental health impacts — PTSD, depression, anxiety (1)\n• Diversion of resources from health and education to military (1)\n• Long-term development setback — infrastructure, institutions, human capital destroyed (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of trade in promoting or hindering development.', marks: 6, markScheme: '• Trade can drive economic growth — export revenue funds development (1)\n• Access to global markets provides opportunities for developing countries (1)\n• However, terms of trade often unfavourable — low commodity prices (1)\n• Trade liberalisation can destroy local industries unable to compete (1)\n• Dependency on primary commodity exports creates vulnerability (1)\n• Fair trade movement attempts to address power imbalances (1)\n• Trade agreements may include conditions that limit policy autonomy (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain the challenges of measuring human rights.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Human rights are qualitative and difficult to quantify (1)\n• Governments may suppress information about violations (1)\n• Cultural relativism — different societies prioritise different rights (1)\n• Economic vs civil/political rights — which to measure and prioritise? (1)\n• Data collection in conflict zones is extremely difficult (1)' },
      { q: 'Explain how water and sanitation affect health outcomes.', marks: 4, markScheme: '• Contaminated water causes diarrhoeal diseases — leading killer of children under 5 (1)\n• Poor sanitation enables spread of cholera, typhoid, parasitic infections (1)\n• Water collection (often by women/girls) reduces time for education and work (1)\n• Investment in WASH (Water, Sanitation, Hygiene) is one of most cost-effective health interventions (1)' },

      // 8-9 mark questions (10)
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which economic development is the key to improving global health.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Balanced assessment weighing economic development against other factors.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nEconomic development as key:\n• Higher GDP enables greater healthcare spending\n• Better nutrition and living conditions reduce disease\n• Education correlates with better health outcomes\n• Infrastructure development improves water, sanitation, transport\n• Epidemiological transition demonstrates link between development and health patterns\n• Life expectancy strongly correlated with GDP per capita\nOther factors:\n• Governance quality matters more than wealth — some low-income countries achieve good health outcomes e.g. Cuba, Sri Lanka\n• Targeted health interventions can succeed without broad economic development\n• Cultural factors affect health-seeking behaviour\n• Conflict negates development gains\n• Inequality within countries means growth doesnt automatically improve health for all\n• Environmental factors independent of development\nConclusion: economic development is important but not sufficient — governance, equality and targeted interventions equally important.' },
      { q: 'Assess the effectiveness of international intervention in protecting human rights.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific case study examples of intervention.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nEffective examples:\n• Kosovo 1999 — NATO intervention stopped ethnic cleansing\n• Sierra Leone — UK/UN intervention ended civil war\n• East Timor — international support for independence\n• International Criminal Court — prosecuting war criminals\nIneffective/harmful examples:\n• Libya 2011 — regime change led to ongoing instability\n• Iraq 2003 — WMD justification undermined legitimacy, created chaos\n• Rwanda 1994 — failure to intervene during genocide\n• Syria — international community unable to agree on action\n• Somalia — intervention failed and withdrew\nChallenges:\n• Selective application — not all crises addressed equally\n• Sovereignty vs intervention tension unresolved\n• Security Council veto prevents action when major powers disagree\n• Unintended consequences often severe\n• Intervention without post-conflict planning fails\nConclusion: mixed record — intervention can protect rights but carries significant risks and is applied inconsistently.' },
      { q: 'Assess the view that globalisation has improved health outcomes worldwide.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment considering positive and negative health impacts of globalisation.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nImproved health:\n• Global sharing of medical knowledge and technology\n• International pharmaceutical companies developing treatments\n• Vaccination programmes reaching more people\n• Economic growth funding healthcare in developing countries\n• Communication technology enabling telemedicine\n• Global health initiatives — WHO, GAVI, Global Fund\nWorsened health:\n• Spread of NCDs through Western diet and lifestyle (obesity, diabetes)\n• Tobacco and alcohol marketing targeting developing countries\n• Brain drain of healthcare workers from poor to rich countries\n• Pandemics spread rapidly through global connectivity\n• Environmental degradation affecting health\n• Fast food culture replacing traditional diets\n• Pharmaceutical patents keeping medicines expensive\nConclusion: globalisation has improved health on average but created new challenges and inequalities — benefits not equally distributed.' },
      { q: 'Assess the challenges of achieving universal human rights.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of multiple challenges with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Cultural relativism — some societies prioritise collective over individual rights\n• State sovereignty limits international enforcement\n• Economic costs — rights like healthcare and education require resources\n• Authoritarian governments resist external pressure\n• Western dominance in defining rights — accusations of cultural imperialism\n• Conflict zones where rights are systematically violated\n• Gender inequality deeply embedded in many societies\n• Poverty makes many rights inaccessible in practice\n• Contradictions between different rights — security vs liberty\n• Enforcement mechanisms weak at international level\n• Selective application by powerful nations undermines credibility\n• Progress is real but slow and uneven' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of TNCs in either promoting or undermining development.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment with specific examples of TNC impacts.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nPromoting development:\n• Employment creation and income generation\n• Technology and skills transfer\n• Infrastructure investment\n• Tax revenue for host governments\n• Integration into global supply chains\n• Example: Samsung in Vietnam creating major manufacturing sector\nUndermining development:\n• Profit repatriation reduces local economic benefit\n• Tax avoidance through transfer pricing\n• Worker exploitation — low wages, poor conditions\n• Environmental damage in countries with weak regulation\n• Displacing local businesses unable to compete\n• Political influence undermining governance\n• Resource extraction without fair compensation\n• Example: extractive industries in Niger Delta\nConclusion: TNCs can promote or undermine development depending on governance framework, regulation and the specific sector involved.' },
      { q: 'Assess the extent to which direct military intervention achieves its aims.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment with specific case studies evaluating outcomes.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant examples.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nSuccessful:\n• Kosovo 1999 — ethnic cleansing stopped, stability gradually restored\n• Sierra Leone 2000 — UK intervention helped end civil war\n• First Gulf War 1991 — Kuwait liberated from Iraqi occupation\n• Initial stated aims often achieved — regime change, stopping atrocities\nUnsuccessful:\n• Iraq 2003 — regime removed but followed by years of insurgency, sectarian conflict\n• Libya 2011 — Gaddafi removed but country descended into civil war\n• Afghanistan 2001-2021 — Taliban returned after 20-year intervention\n• Somalia 1993 — intervention failed, forces withdrew\nKey factors:\n• Clear objectives increase success likelihood\n• Post-conflict planning essential\n• Local legitimacy and support needed\n• International consensus improves sustainability\n• Exit strategy vital\n• Nation-building is far harder than military victory\nConclusion: intervention can achieve short-term military aims but rarely delivers long-term political stability — track record mixed at best.' },
      { q: 'Assess the geographical factors that influence patterns of disease globally.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment of geographical factors with specific disease examples.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Climate — tropical climates support mosquito-borne diseases (malaria, dengue, Zika)\n• Water availability — water scarcity limits sanitation, water-borne diseases\n• Latitude — seasonal patterns affect disease transmission\n• Altitude — affects vector range for diseases like malaria\n• Urbanisation — crowding facilitates communicable disease spread\n• Isolation — remote communities may lack healthcare access\n• Natural disasters — earthquakes, floods create disease outbreaks\n• However, human factors interact with geography:\n• Economic development can overcome geographical disadvantages\n• Technology (air conditioning, mosquito nets) modify geographical effects\n• Migration and trade spread diseases beyond their geographical origins\n• Climate change altering disease geography — tropical diseases spreading poleward' },
      { q: 'Assess the effectiveness of different types of development aid in improving health.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Balanced assessment of different aid types with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements about aid.\n\nIndicative content:\nBilateral aid:\n• Government to government — can be large-scale\n• May be tied to donor country interests\n• Variable effectiveness depending on governance\nMultilateral aid:\n• Through WHO, World Bank, GAVI\n• Better coordination but bureaucratic\n• Global Fund for AIDS, TB, Malaria — significant impact\nNGO aid:\n• MSF, Red Cross — targeted and flexible\n• Community-based and responsive\n• Limited scale and sustainability\nSpecific health programmes:\n• Vaccination campaigns — huge success (smallpox eradication, polio near-eradication)\n• Mosquito net distribution — reduced malaria mortality\n• PEPFAR (US) — major impact on HIV/AIDS\nCritiques:\n• Aid dependency undermines local health systems\n• Vertical programmes neglect overall system strengthening\n• Corruption diverts aid from intended purposes\n• Short-term projects vs sustainable long-term investment\nConclusion: targeted health interventions show strong results but need to be combined with health system strengthening for lasting impact.' },
      { q: 'Assess the role of education in improving health and human rights.', marks: 8, markScheme: 'Level 3 (6-8 marks): Thorough assessment linking education to both health and rights outcomes.\nLevel 2 (3-5 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-2 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nHealth benefits:\n• Health literacy — understanding of disease prevention and treatment\n• Educated mothers have healthier children — lower child mortality\n• Education enables higher income — better nutrition, healthcare access\n• Reduced risky behaviours — safer sex, less substance abuse\n• Ability to access and understand health information\nHuman rights benefits:\n• Awareness of rights enables people to claim them\n• Education itself is a fundamental human right\n• Empowers marginalised groups — women, minorities\n• Enables political participation and civic engagement\n• Reduces vulnerability to exploitation\nLimitations:\n• Education alone insufficient without economic opportunities\n• Quality of education matters — not just access\n• Cultural barriers may persist despite education\n• Education systems may reinforce existing inequalities\n• Takes a generation to see full effects\nConclusion: education is arguably the single most important investment for improving both health and rights — but needs to be quality education within a supportive policy environment.' },
      { q: 'Assess the impact of climate change on global health patterns.', marks: 9, markScheme: 'Level 3 (7-9 marks): Thorough assessment of multiple health impacts with specific examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some assessment with relevant points.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\n• Vector-borne diseases expanding range — malaria, dengue moving to higher altitudes/latitudes\n• Heat-related mortality increasing — heatwaves more frequent and intense\n• Food insecurity — crop failures affecting nutrition\n• Water stress — reduced access to clean water\n• Air pollution worsened by higher temperatures\n• Mental health impacts — eco-anxiety, climate displacement\n• Natural disasters — flooding, storms causing injury and disease outbreaks\n• Disproportionate impact on developing countries and vulnerable populations\n• Existing health inequalities amplified\n• However, some areas may see reduced cold-related mortality\n• Health systems in developed countries better able to adapt\n• WHO estimates 250,000 additional deaths per year between 2030-2050\n• Climate change as a "threat multiplier" for existing health challenges' },

      // 12-20 mark questions (5)
      { q: 'Evaluate the view that human rights are universal and should be applied equally in all countries.', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with balanced argument considering universalism and cultural relativism.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nUniversal rights argument:\n• Universal Declaration of Human Rights (1948) — agreed by most nations\n• Fundamental rights should transcend cultural boundaries — dignity, life, freedom from torture\n• Without universality, any abuse can be justified by culture\n• Many within non-Western cultures advocate for the same rights\n• International law provides framework for accountability\n• Globalisation makes universal standards more practical\nCultural relativism argument:\n• UDHR was drafted primarily by Western nations — reflects Western values\n• Different societies have different concepts of rights — collective vs individual\n• Imposing external standards is a form of cultural imperialism\n• Asian values debate — some argue rights must be contextualised\n• Religious and traditional legal systems may conflict with international standards\n• Sovereignty means states should determine their own values\nNuance:\n• Some rights may be more universal than others\n• Implementation can be contextualised while maintaining core principles\n• Dialogue between cultures needed rather than imposition\n• Women rights often at the centre of this debate\nConclusion should engage with the complexity — some core rights (life, freedom from torture) are harder to contest than others — the challenge is finding balance between universal principles and cultural context.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the effectiveness of international strategies to combat communicable diseases.', marks: 16, markScheme: 'Level 4 (13-16 marks): Comprehensive evaluation with detailed case studies of different disease strategies. Well-structured argument.\nLevel 3 (9-12 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (5-8 marks): Some evaluation with limited range.\nLevel 1 (1-4 marks): Basic descriptive points.\n\nIndicative content:\nSuccesses:\n• Smallpox eradication (1980) — proof that diseases can be eliminated globally\n• Polio near-eradication — cases reduced by 99% since 1988\n• HIV/AIDS — antiretroviral therapy dramatically reduced mortality, PEPFAR programme\n• Malaria — bed nets and ACTs reduced deaths by 60% since 2000\n• COVID-19 vaccines developed in record time\n• GAVI Alliance vaccinating millions in developing countries\nChallenges:\n• COVID-19 pandemic exposed weaknesses in global health governance\n• Vaccine inequality — COVAX fell short of targets\n• Antimicrobial resistance — growing threat\n• Emerging infectious diseases — Ebola, Zika, novel coronaviruses\n• Funding gaps and donor fatigue\n• Weak health systems in developing countries limit implementation\n• Political obstacles — anti-vaccine movements, misinformation\n• Endemic diseases continue to kill — TB kills 1.5 million per year\nStrategies to evaluate:\n• WHO coordination and surveillance\n• Vertical programmes (disease-specific) vs horizontal (health system) strengthening\n• Public-private partnerships\n• Community health workers\n• Research and development investment\nConclusion: significant progress but emerging threats and inequality in access mean the job is far from complete — pandemic preparedness and health system strengthening are priorities.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the statement: "International intervention does more harm than good."', marks: 12, markScheme: 'Level 4 (10-12 marks): Thorough evaluation with balanced case study evidence.\nLevel 3 (7-9 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (4-6 marks): Some evaluation but may be one-sided.\nLevel 1 (1-3 marks): Basic statements.\n\nIndicative content:\nMore harm:\n• Iraq 2003 — regime change led to insurgency, ISIS, hundreds of thousands of deaths\n• Libya 2011 — power vacuum, civil war, migrant crisis\n• Afghanistan — 20-year intervention ended with Taliban return\n• Civilian casualties in drone strikes and bombing campaigns\n• Destruction of infrastructure set back development\n• Creates resentment and anti-Western sentiment\n• Often motivated by self-interest not humanitarianism\nMore good:\n• Kosovo 1999 — prevented further ethnic cleansing\n• Sierra Leone — UK intervention ended brutal civil war\n• East Timor — international support for self-determination\n• Humanitarian aid saves lives in disasters and famines\n• Peacekeeping missions maintain stability in fragile states\n• International sanctions (economic intervention) pressured apartheid South Africa\nNon-military intervention:\n• Development aid — mixed record but some successes\n• Diplomatic intervention — negotiation and mediation\n• Economic sanctions — can pressure change without military action\nConclusion: the record is genuinely mixed — success depends on legitimacy, planning, international consensus and post-intervention commitment. Blanket statements in either direction are unhelpful.' },
      { q: 'Discuss the relationship between health, human rights and economic development.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive discussion demonstrating sophisticated understanding of the interrelationships. Detailed evidence from multiple contexts.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good discussion with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some relevant discussion but may lack depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nHealth and development:\n• Better health increases workforce productivity and economic output\n• Healthy children perform better in education — future human capital\n• Reduced disease burden frees government resources for development\n• Epidemiological transition shows health patterns change with development\n• However, development can bring new health challenges — NCDs, pollution\n• Health inequality within developed countries shows GDP alone insufficient\nHuman rights and development:\n• Rights to education and healthcare support human capital development\n• Political freedoms enable good governance and accountability\n• Property rights encourage investment and economic activity\n• Gender equality correlated with stronger economic growth\n• However, some authoritarian states have achieved rapid development (China)\n• Rights may be sacrificed in pursuit of economic growth\nHealth and human rights:\n• Health is a human right (Article 25, UDHR)\n• Rights abuses cause health problems — torture, conflict, discrimination\n• Gender inequality directly affects health outcomes for women\n• Access to healthcare depends on rights to non-discrimination\n• Environmental rights linked to health outcomes\nCase studies:\n• Nordic countries — high rights, high health, high development\n• Cuba — good health despite limited economic development and restricted political rights\n• Sub-Saharan Africa — where development, rights and health challenges intersect\n• China — economic development with restricted rights\n• USA — wealthy but significant health inequalities\nConclusion should argue these three dimensions are fundamentally interconnected — progress in one supports progress in others, and failure in one undermines the rest. Sustainable development requires attention to all three dimensions simultaneously.' },
      { q: 'Evaluate the extent to which global governance is effective in addressing health and human rights challenges.', marks: 20, markScheme: 'Level 4 (16-20 marks): Comprehensive evaluation of multiple governance mechanisms with detailed evidence. Sophisticated argument about effectiveness and limitations.\nLevel 3 (11-15 marks): Good evaluation with relevant examples.\nLevel 2 (6-10 marks): Some evaluation with limited depth.\nLevel 1 (1-5 marks): Basic descriptive content.\n\nIndicative content:\nHealth governance:\n• WHO — coordinates international health responses, sets standards\n• COVID-19 pandemic tested and exposed weaknesses in WHO governance\n• International Health Regulations — legally binding but poorly enforced\n• GAVI, Global Fund — public-private partnerships showing results\n• Pandemic preparedness gaps revealed by COVID-19\n• Vaccine nationalism vs equitable distribution\n• Success in disease-specific programmes (polio, malaria, HIV)\nHuman rights governance:\n• UN Human Rights Council — monitoring and reporting\n• International Criminal Court — accountability for worst crimes\n• Treaty monitoring bodies — oversight but limited enforcement\n• Responsibility to Protect — principle but inconsistent application\n• Sanctions regimes — economic pressure for change\n• Success in raising awareness and setting norms\nEffectiveness assessment:\n• Strengths: global standards established, some enforcement mechanisms, coordination improved\n• Weaknesses: sovereignty limits intervention, Security Council veto blocks action, enforcement weak, powerful states exempt themselves\n• Selective application undermines legitimacy\n• Funding gaps limit programme delivery\n• Political polarisation weakening multilateralism\n• Non-state actors (NGOs, TNCs) increasingly important alongside states\n• COVID-19 showed both necessity and limitations of global governance\nConclusion: global governance has achieved significant progress in both health and rights but remains inadequate to address the scale of challenges — reform needed to make institutions more representative, better funded and more effective at enforcement.' },
    ],
  },
};
